02497 /**
02498  * cvmx_mio_boot_bist_stat
02499  *
02500  * The boot BIST status register contains the BIST status for the MIO boot memories: 0 = pass, 1
02501  * = fail.
02502  */
02503 union cvmx_mio_boot_bist_stat {
02504     uint64_t u64;
02505     struct cvmx_mio_boot_bist_stat_s {
02506 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02507     uint64_t reserved_0_63                : 64;
02508 #else
02509     uint64_t reserved_0_63                : 64;
02510 #endif
02511     } s;
02512     struct cvmx_mio_boot_bist_stat_cn30xx {
02513 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02514     uint64_t reserved_4_63                : 60;
02515     uint64_t ncbo_1                       : 1;  /**< NCB output FIFO 1 BIST status */
02516     uint64_t ncbo_0                       : 1;  /**< NCB output FIFO 0 BIST status */
02517     uint64_t loc                          : 1;  /**< Local memory BIST status */
02518     uint64_t ncbi                         : 1;  /**< NCB input FIFO BIST status */
02519 #else
02520     uint64_t ncbi                         : 1;
02521     uint64_t loc                          : 1;
02522     uint64_t ncbo_0                       : 1;
02523     uint64_t ncbo_1                       : 1;
02524     uint64_t reserved_4_63                : 60;
02525 #endif
02526     } cn30xx;
02527     struct cvmx_mio_boot_bist_stat_cn30xx cn31xx;
02528     struct cvmx_mio_boot_bist_stat_cn38xx {
02529 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02530     uint64_t reserved_3_63                : 61;
02531     uint64_t ncbo_0                       : 1;  /**< NCB output FIFO BIST status */
02532     uint64_t loc                          : 1;  /**< Local memory BIST status */
02533     uint64_t ncbi                         : 1;  /**< NCB input FIFO BIST status */
02534 #else
02535     uint64_t ncbi                         : 1;
02536     uint64_t loc                          : 1;
02537     uint64_t ncbo_0                       : 1;
02538     uint64_t reserved_3_63                : 61;
02539 #endif
02540     } cn38xx;
02541     struct cvmx_mio_boot_bist_stat_cn38xx cn38xxp2;
02542     struct cvmx_mio_boot_bist_stat_cn50xx {
02543 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD

02721 /**
02722  * cvmx_mio_boot_ctl
02723  *
02724  * The hardware allows only one controller to use the BootBus and the MIO_NDF_DMA engine
02725  * at a time.  The SEL field determines the owner.
02726  * This field should be changed only when the current controller operations are complete.
02727  * Here are several situations.
02728  *    1.  If eMMC/SD is currently doing a read or write command without a DMA then the
02729  *        MIO_EMM_INT[CMD_DONE] should occur before SEL is changed.
02730  *    2.  If eMMC/SD is currently doing a dma operation with the device then the
02731  *        MIO_EMM_INT[DMA_DONE] should occur before SEL is changed.  Care must be taken not to
02732  *        reprogram the MIO_NDF_DMA_CFG register until both the previous MIO_NDF_DMA_INT[DONE]
02733  *        has occurred and the new SEL has been set.
02734  *    3.  If NAND is currently doing one or more operations to the external device without using
02735  *        the DMA then the NDF_INT[EMPTY] should occur to guarantee all commands are executed
02736  *        before changing the SEL value.
02737  *    4.  If NAND is currently doing one or more operations to the external device which includes
02738  *        DMAs then the SEL should not change until both the last MIO_NDF_DMA_INT[DONE] and
02739  *        NDF_INT[EMPTY] have occurred.
02740  */
02741 union cvmx_mio_boot_ctl {
02742     uint64_t u64;
02743     struct cvmx_mio_boot_ctl_s {
02744 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02745     uint64_t reserved_1_63                : 63;
02746     uint64_t sel                          : 1;  /**< Controller Selection.
02747                                                          0 = eMMC/SD,
02748                                                          1 = NAND */
02749 #else
02750     uint64_t sel                          : 1;
02751     uint64_t reserved_1_63                : 63;
02752 #endif
02753     } s;
02754     struct cvmx_mio_boot_ctl_s            cn70xx;
02755     struct cvmx_mio_boot_ctl_s            cn70xxp1;
02756 };
02757 typedef union cvmx_mio_boot_ctl cvmx_mio_boot_ctl_t;
02758

02771                                                          if WIDTH=0, 32-bit aligned if WIDTH=1). */

02784 /**
02785  * cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfg#
02786  *
02787  * This is the DMA engine n configuration register (one register for each of two engines).
02788  * Care must be taken to insure that the DMA duration not exceed the processor timeout of 2^29
02789  * core clocks or the RML timeout specified in SLI_WINDOW_CTL[TIME] coprocessor clocks if
02790  * accesses to the boot bus occur while DMA operations are in progress.
02791  * The DMA operation duration in coprocessor clocks as:
02792  * MIO_BOOT_DMA_CFG()[SIZE] * MIO_BOOT_DMA_TIM()[TIM_MULT] * CYCLE_TIME.
02793  * Where:
02794  * CYCLE_TIME = MIO_BOOT_DMA_TIM()[RD_DLY+PAUSE+DMACK_H+WE_N+WE_A+OE_N+OE_A+DMACK_S].
02795  * Coprocessor clocks can be converted to core clocks by multiplying the value by the clock ratio
02796  * RST_BOOT[C_MUL] / RST_BOOT[PNR_MUL].
02797  */
02798 union cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfgx {
02799     uint64_t u64;
02800     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfgx_s {
02801 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02802     uint64_t en                           : 1;  /**< DMA engine 0-1 enable. */
02803     uint64_t rw                           : 1;  /**< DMA engine 0-1 R/W bit (0 = read, 1 = write). */
02804     uint64_t clr                          : 1;  /**< DMA engine 0-1 clear EN on device terminated burst. */
02805     uint64_t reserved_60_60               : 1;
02806     uint64_t swap32                       : 1;  /**< DMA engine 0-1 32-bit swap. */
02807     uint64_t swap16                       : 1;  /**< DMA engine 0-1 16-bit swap. */
02808     uint64_t swap8                        : 1;  /**< DMA engine 0-1 8-bit swap. */
02809     uint64_t endian                       : 1;  /**< DMA engine 0-1 IOB endian mode (0 = big, 1 = little). */
02810     uint64_t size                         : 20; /**< DMA engine 0-1 size. SIZE is specified in number of bus transfers, where one transfer is
02811                                                          equal to the following number of bytes, dependent on MIO_BOOT_DMA_TIM()[WIDTH] and
02812                                                          MIO_BOOT_DMA_TIM()[DDR]:
02813                                                          _ If WIDTH=0, DDR=0, then transfer is 2 bytes.
02814                                                          _ If WIDTH=0, DDR=1, then transfer is 4 bytes.
02815                                                          _ If WIDTH=1, DDR=0, then transfer is 4 bytes.
02816                                                          _ If WIDTH=1, DDR=1, then transfer is 8 bytes. */
02817     uint64_t adr                          : 36; /**< DMA Engine X address */
02818 #else
02819     uint64_t adr                          : 36;
02820     uint64_t size                         : 20;
02821     uint64_t endian                       : 1;
02822     uint64_t swap8                        : 1;
02823     uint64_t swap16                       : 1;
02824     uint64_t swap32                       : 1;
02825     uint64_t reserved_60_60               : 1;
02826     uint64_t clr                          : 1;
02827     uint64_t rw                           : 1;
02828     uint64_t en                           : 1;
02829 #endif
02830     } s;
02831     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfgx_s       cn52xx;
02832     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfgx_s       cn52xxp1;
02833     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfgx_s       cn56xx;
02834     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfgx_s       cn56xxp1;
02835     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfgx_s       cn61xx;
02836     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfgx_s       cn63xx;
02837     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfgx_s       cn63xxp1;
02838     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfgx_s       cn66xx;
02839     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfgx_s       cn68xx;
02840     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfgx_s       cn68xxp1;
02841     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfgx_cn73xx {
02842 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02843     uint64_t en                           : 1;  /**< DMA engine 0-1 enable. */
02844     uint64_t rw                           : 1;  /**< DMA engine 0-1 R/W bit (0 = read, 1 = write). */
02845     uint64_t clr                          : 1;  /**< DMA engine 0-1 clear EN on device terminated burst. */
02846     uint64_t reserved_60_60               : 1;
02847     uint64_t swap32                       : 1;  /**< DMA engine 0-1 32-bit swap. */
02848     uint64_t swap16                       : 1;  /**< DMA engine 0-1 16-bit swap. */
02849     uint64_t swap8                        : 1;  /**< DMA engine 0-1 8-bit swap. */
02850     uint64_t endian                       : 1;  /**< DMA engine 0-1 IOB endian mode (0 = big, 1 = little). */
02851     uint64_t size                         : 20; /**< DMA engine 0-1 size. SIZE is specified in number of bus transfers, where one transfer is
02852                                                          equal to the following number of bytes, dependent on MIO_BOOT_DMA_TIM()[WIDTH] and
02853                                                          MIO_BOOT_DMA_TIM()[DDR]:
02854                                                          _ If WIDTH=0, DDR=0, then transfer is 2 bytes.
02855                                                          _ If WIDTH=0, DDR=1, then transfer is 4 bytes.
02856                                                          _ If WIDTH=1, DDR=0, then transfer is 4 bytes.
02857                                                          _ If WIDTH=1, DDR=1, then transfer is 8 bytes. */
02858     uint64_t reserved_0_35                : 36;
02859 #else
02860     uint64_t reserved_0_35                : 36;
02861     uint64_t size                         : 20;
02862     uint64_t endian                       : 1;
02863     uint64_t swap8                        : 1;
02864     uint64_t swap16                       : 1;
02865     uint64_t swap32                       : 1;
02866     uint64_t reserved_60_60               : 1;
02867     uint64_t clr                          : 1;
02868     uint64_t rw                           : 1;
02869     uint64_t en                           : 1;
02870 #endif
02871     } cn73xx;
02872     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfgx_cn73xx  cn78xx;
02873     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfgx_cn73xx  cn78xxp1;
02874     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfgx_s       cnf71xx;
02875     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfgx_cn73xx  cnf75xx;
02876 };
02877 typedef union cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfgx cvmx_mio_boot_dma_cfgx_t;

02974 /**
02975  * cvmx_mio_boot_dma_tim#
02976  *
02977  * This is the DMA engine n timing register (one register for each of two engines).
02978  *
02979  */
02980 union cvmx_mio_boot_dma_timx {
02981     uint64_t u64;
02982     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_timx_s {
02983 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02984     uint64_t dmack_pi                     : 1;  /**< DMA acknowledgment polarity inversion. [DMACK_PI] inverts the assertion level of
02985                                                          BOOT_DMACKn. The default polarity of BOOT_DMACK<1:0> is selected on the first deassertion
02986                                                          of reset by the values on BOOT_AD<12:11>, where 0 specifies active high and 1 specifies
02987                                                          active low. (See MIO_BOOT_PIN_DEFS for a read-only copy of the default polarity.)
02988                                                          BOOT_AD<12:11> have internal pull-down resistors, so place a pull-up resistor on
02989                                                          BOOT_AD<n+11> for active low default polarity on engine n. To interface with CF cards in
02990                                                          True IDE Mode, either a pull-up resistor should be placed on BOOT_AD<n+11> OR the
02991                                                          corresponding DMACK_PI<n> should be set. */
02992     uint64_t dmarq_pi                     : 1;  /**< DMA request polarity inversion. [DMARQ_PI] inverts the assertion level of BOOT_DMARQn. The
02993                                                          default polarity of BOOT_DMARQ<1:0> is active high, so that setting the polarity inversion
02994                                                          bits changes the polarity to active low. To interface with CF cards in True IDE Mode, the
02995                                                          corresponding DMARQ_PI<n> should be clear. */
02996     uint64_t tim_mult                     : 2;  /**< Timing multiplier. This field specifies the timing multiplier for an engine. The timing
02997                                                          multiplier applies to all timing parameters, except for [DMARQ] and [RD_DLY], which simply
02998                                                          count coprocessor-clock cycles. [TIM_MULT] is encoded as follows:
02999                                                          0x0 = 4*.
03000                                                          0x1 = 1*.
03001                                                          0x2 = 2*.
03002                                                          0x3 = 8*. */
03003     uint64_t rd_dly                       : 3;  /**< Read sample delay. This field specifies the read sample delay in coprocessor-clock cycles
03004                                                          for an engine. For read operations, the data bus is normally sampled on the same
03005                                                          coprocessor-clock edge that drives BOOT_OE_L high (and also low in DDR mode). This
03006                                                          parameter can delay that sampling edge by up to seven coprocessor-clock cycles.
03007                                                          The number of coprocessor-clock cycles counted by the [OE_A] and [DMACK_H] + [PAUSE]
03008                                                          timing
03009                                                          parameters must be greater than [RD_DLY]. */
03010     uint64_t ddr                          : 1;  /**< DDR mode. If DDR is set, then [WE_N] must be less than [WE_A]. */
03011     uint64_t width                        : 1;  /**< Bus width (0 = 16 bits, 1 = 32 bits). */
03012     uint64_t reserved_48_54               : 7;
03013     uint64_t pause                        : 6;  /**< Pause count. */
03014     uint64_t dmack_h                      : 6;  /**< DMA acknowledgment hold count. */
03015     uint64_t we_n                         : 6;  /**< Write enable negated count. */
03016     uint64_t we_a                         : 6;  /**< Write enable asserted count. */
03017     uint64_t oe_n                         : 6;  /**< Output enable negated count. */
03018     uint64_t oe_a                         : 6;  /**< Output enable asserted count. */
03019     uint64_t dmack_s                      : 6;  /**< DMA acknowledgment setup count. */
03020     uint64_t dmarq                        : 6;  /**< DMA request count. (Must be nonzero.) */
03021 #else
03022     uint64_t dmarq                        : 6;
03023     uint64_t dmack_s                      : 6;
03024     uint64_t oe_a                         : 6;
03025     uint64_t oe_n                         : 6;
03026     uint64_t we_a                         : 6;
03027     uint64_t we_n                         : 6;
03028     uint64_t dmack_h                      : 6;
03029     uint64_t pause                        : 6;
03030     uint64_t reserved_48_54               : 7;
03031     uint64_t width                        : 1;
03032     uint64_t ddr                          : 1;
03033     uint64_t rd_dly                       : 3;
03034     uint64_t tim_mult                     : 2;
03035     uint64_t dmarq_pi                     : 1;
03036     uint64_t dmack_pi                     : 1;
03037 #endif
03038     } s;
03039     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_timx_s       cn52xx;
03040     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_timx_s       cn52xxp1;
03041     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_timx_s       cn56xx;
03042     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_timx_s       cn56xxp1;
03043     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_timx_s       cn61xx;
03044     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_timx_s       cn63xx;
03045     struct cvmx_mio_boot_dma_timx_s       cn63xxp1;

03565 /**
03566  * cvmx_mio_boot_reg_cfg#
03567  *
03568  * The region n configuration register (one register for each of seven regions) contains
03569  * configuration parameters for boot region n.
03570  */
03571 union cvmx_mio_boot_reg_cfgx {
03572     uint64_t u64;
03573     struct cvmx_mio_boot_reg_cfgx_s {
03574 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03575     uint64_t reserved_44_63               : 20;
03576     uint64_t dmack                        : 2;  /**< Region 1-7 DMACK. If nonzero, this field asserts the corresponding BOOT_DMACK<n> pin when
03577                                                          an access to this region is performed. DMACK is encoded as follows:
03578                                                          0x0 = disabled.
03579                                                          0x1 = BOOT_DMACK<0>.
03580                                                          0x2 = BOOT_DMACK<1>.
03581                                                          0x3 = BOOT_DMACK<2>.
03582                                                          This is useful for CF cards in PC card memory mode that support DMA because the -REG and
03583                                                          -DMACK pins are shared.
03584                                                          The assertion level of BOOT_DMACK is specified by MIO_BOOT_DMA_TIM()[DMACK_PI]. */
03585     uint64_t tim_mult                     : 2;  /**< Region 1-7 timing multiplier. Specifies the timing multiplier for a region. The timing
03586                                                          multiplier applies to all timing parameters, except for WAIT and RD_DLY, which simply
03587                                                          count coprocessor-clock cycles. TIM_MULT is encoded as follows:
03588                                                          0x0 = 4*.
03589                                                          0x1 = 1*.
03590                                                          0x2 = 2*.
03591                                                          0x3 = 8*. */
03592     uint64_t rd_dly                       : 3;  /**< Region 1-7 read sample delay. Specifies the read sample delay in coprocessor-clock cycles
03593                                                          for a region. For read operations, the data bus is normally sampled on the same
03594                                                          coprocessor-clock edge that drives BOOT_OE_L to the inactive state (or the coprocessor-
03595                                                          clock edge that toggles the lower address bits in page mode). This parameter can delay
03596                                                          that sampling edge by up to seven coprocessor-clock cycles.
03597                                                          The number of coprocessor-clock cycles counted by the PAGE and RD_HLD timing parameters
03598                                                          must be greater than or equal to RD_DLY. */
03599     uint64_t sam                          : 1;  /**< Region 1-7 strobe AND mode. Internally combines the output-enable and write-enable strobes
03600                                                          into a single strobe that is then driven onto both BOOT_OE_L and BOOT_WE_L.
03601                                                          This is useful for parts that use a single strobe along with a read/write bit (the
03602                                                          read/write bit can be driven from an address pin). */
03603     uint64_t we_ext                       : 2;  /**< Region 1-7 write-enable count extension. */
03604     uint64_t oe_ext                       : 2;  /**< Region 1-7 output-enable count extension. */
03605     uint64_t en                           : 1;  /**< Region 1-7 enable. */
03606     uint64_t orbit                        : 1;  /**< Region 1-7 ORBIT bit. Asserts the given region's chip enable when there is an address hit
03607                                                          in the previous region.
03608                                                          This is useful for CF cards because it allows the use of 2 separate timing configurations
03609                                                          for common memory and attribute memory. */
03610     uint64_t ale                          : 1;  /**< Region 1-7 address-latch-enable mode. Enables the multiplexed address/data bus mode. The
03611                                                          reset value for region 0 is the value of BOOT_AD[15] on the deassertion of reset. */
03612     uint64_t width                        : 1;  /**< Region 1-7 bus width:
03613                                                          0 = 8 bits.
03614                                                          1 = 16 bits.
03615                                                          The reset value for region 0 is the value of BOOT_AD<14> on the deassertion of reset. */
03616     uint64_t size                         : 12; /**< Region 1-7 size. Region size is specified in 64K blocks and in 'block-1' notation (i.e.
03617                                                          0x0 = one 64K block, 0x1 = two 64K blocks, etc.). */
03618     uint64_t base                         : 16; /**< Region 1-7 base address. Specifies address bits <31:16> of the first 64K block of the
03619                                                          region. */
03620 #else
03621     uint64_t base                         : 16;
03622     uint64_t size                         : 12;
03623     uint64_t width                        : 1;
03624     uint64_t ale                          : 1;
03625     uint64_t orbit                        : 1;
03626     uint64_t en                           : 1;
03627     uint64_t oe_ext                       : 2;
03628     uint64_t we_ext                       : 2;
03629     uint64_t sam                          : 1;
03630     uint64_t rd_dly                       : 3;
03631     uint64_t tim_mult                     : 2;
03632     uint64_t dmack                        : 2;
03633     uint64_t reserved_44_63               : 20;
03634 #endif
03635     } s;

03637 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03638     uint64_t reserved_37_63               : 27;

03640     uint64_t we_ext                       : 2;  /**< Region X write enable count extension */
03641     uint64_t oe_ext                       : 2;  /**< Region X output enable count extension */

03731 /**
03732  * cvmx_mio_boot_reg_tim#
03733  *
03734  * The region n timing register (one register for each of seven regions) contains page-mode,
03735  * wait-mode, and timing parameters for region n.
03736  */
03737 union cvmx_mio_boot_reg_timx {
03738     uint64_t u64;
03739     struct cvmx_mio_boot_reg_timx_s {
03740 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03741     uint64_t pagem                        : 1;  /**< Region 1-7 page mode. */
03742     uint64_t waitm                        : 1;  /**< Region 1-7 wait mode. */
03743     uint64_t pages                        : 2;  /**< Region 1-7 page size:
03744                                                          0x0 = 8 bytes.
03745                                                          0x1 = 2 bytes.
03746                                                          0x2 = 4 bytes.
03747                                                          0x3 = 8 bytes. */
03748     uint64_t ale                          : 6;  /**< Region 1-7 ALE count. Must be nonzero to ensure legal transitions on the corresponding
03749                                                          boot bus outputs. */
03750     uint64_t page                         : 6;  /**< Region 1-7 page count. Must be nonzero to ensure legal transitions on the corresponding
03751                                                          boot bus outputs. */
03752     uint64_t wait                         : 6;  /**< Region 1-7 wait count, must be nonzero when WAITM is set to 1. */
03753     uint64_t pause                        : 6;  /**< Region 1-7 pause count. */
03754     uint64_t wr_hld                       : 6;  /**< Region 1-7 write-hold count. */
03755     uint64_t rd_hld                       : 6;  /**< Region 1-7 read-hold count. */
03756     uint64_t we                           : 6;  /**< Region 1-7 write-enable count. Must be nonzero to ensure legal transitions on the
03757                                                          corresponding boot bus outputs. */
03758     uint64_t oe                           : 6;  /**< Region 1-7 output-enable count. Must be nonzero to ensure legal transitions on the
03759                                                          corresponding boot bus outputs. */
03760     uint64_t ce                           : 6;  /**< Region 1-7 chip-enable count. */
03761     uint64_t adr                          : 6;  /**< Region 1-7 address count. */
03762 #else
03763     uint64_t adr                          : 6;
03764     uint64_t ce                           : 6;
03765     uint64_t oe                           : 6;
03766     uint64_t we                           : 6;
03767     uint64_t rd_hld                       : 6;
03768     uint64_t wr_hld                       : 6;
03769     uint64_t pause                        : 6;
03770     uint64_t wait                         : 6;
03771     uint64_t page                         : 6;
03772     uint64_t ale                          : 6;
03773     uint64_t pages                        : 2;
03774     uint64_t waitm                        : 1;
03775     uint64_t pagem                        : 1;
03776 #endif
03777     } s;
03778     struct cvmx_mio_boot_reg_timx_s       cn30xx;
03779     struct cvmx_mio_boot_reg_timx_s       cn31xx;

04140 /**
04141  * cvmx_mio_emm_dma
04142  *
04143  * MIO_EMM_DMA = MIO EMMC DMA config Register
04144  *
04145  */
04146 union cvmx_mio_emm_dma {
04147     uint64_t u64;
04148     struct cvmx_mio_emm_dma_s {
04149 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04150     uint64_t reserved_63_63               : 1;
04151     uint64_t skip_busy                    : 1;  /**< Controls when DMA is completed.
04152                                                          0 = DMA doesn't complete until card has dropped the BUSY signal.
04153                                                          1 = Complete DMA after last transfer regardless of the BUSY signal. Status of signal can
04154                                                          be read in MIO_EMM_RSP_STS[RSP_BUSYBIT]. */
04155     uint64_t bus_id                       : 2;  /**< Specify the eMMC bus */
04156     uint64_t dma_val                      : 1;  /**< Software writes this bit to a 1 to indicate that hardware should perform the DMA transfer.
04157                                                          Hardware clears this bit when the DMA operation completes or is terminated. */
04158     uint64_t sector                       : 1;  /**< Specify CARD_ADDR and eMMC are using sector (512 B) addressing. */
04159     uint64_t dat_null                     : 1;  /**< Do not perform any eMMC commands. A DMA read returns all 0s. A DMA write tosses the data.
04160                                                          In the case of a failure, this can be used to unwind the DMA engine. */
04161     uint64_t thres                        : 6;  /**< Number of 8-byte blocks of data that must exist in the DBUF before starting the 512-byte
04162                                                          block transfer. Zero indicates to wait for the entire block. */
04163     uint64_t rel_wr                       : 1;  /**< Set the reliable write parameter when performing CMD23 (SET_BLOCK_COUNT) for a multiple block. */
04164     uint64_t rw                           : 1;  /**< Read/write bit (0 = read, 1 = write). */
04165     uint64_t multi                        : 1;  /**< Perform operation using a multiple block command instead of a series of single block commands. */
04166     uint64_t block_cnt                    : 16; /**< Number of blocks to read/write. Hardware decrements the block count after each successful
04167                                                          block transfer. */
04168     uint64_t card_addr                    : 32; /**< Data address for media <= 2 GB is a 32-bit byte address, and data address for media > 2 GB
04169                                                          is a 32-bit sector (512 B) address. Hardware advances the card address after each
04170                                                          successful block transfer by 512 for byte addressing and by 1 for sector addressing. */
04171 #else
04172     uint64_t card_addr                    : 32;
04173     uint64_t block_cnt                    : 16;
04174     uint64_t multi                        : 1;
04175     uint64_t rw                           : 1;
04176     uint64_t rel_wr                       : 1;
04177     uint64_t thres                        : 6;
04178     uint64_t dat_null                     : 1;
04179     uint64_t sector                       : 1;
04180     uint64_t dma_val                      : 1;
04181     uint64_t bus_id                       : 2;
04182     uint64_t skip_busy                    : 1;
04183     uint64_t reserved_63_63               : 1;
04184 #endif
04185     } s;
04186     struct cvmx_mio_emm_dma_cn61xx {
04187 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04188     uint64_t reserved_62_63               : 2;
04189     uint64_t bus_id                       : 2;  /**< Specify the eMMC bus */
04190     uint64_t dma_val                      : 1;  /**< SW writes this bit to a 1 to indicate that HW should perform
04191                                                          the DMA transfer.   HW clears when DMA operation completes or
04192                                                          is terminated. */
04193     uint64_t sector                       : 1;  /**< Specify CARD_ADDR and eMMC are using sector (512B) addressing. */
04194     uint64_t dat_null                     : 1;  /**< Do not perform any eMMC commands.   A DMA read will return all
04195                                                          0s.  A DMA write tosses the data.  In the case of a failure,
04196                                                          this can be used to unwind the DMA engine. */
04197     uint64_t thres                        : 6;  /**< Number of 8B blocks of data that must exist in the DBUF before
04198                                                          the starting the 512B block transfer.  0 indicates to wait for
04199                                                          the entire block. */
04200     uint64_t rel_wr                       : 1;  /**< Set the reliable write parameter when performing CMD23
04201                                                          (SET_BLOCK_COUNT) for a multiple block */
04202     uint64_t rw                           : 1;  /**< R/W bit (0 = read, 1 = write) */
04203     uint64_t multi                        : 1;  /**< Perform operation using a multiple block command instead of a
04204                                                          series of single block commands. */
04205     uint64_t block_cnt                    : 16; /**< Number of blocks to read/write.  Hardware decrements the block
04206                                                          count after each successful block transfer. */
04207     uint64_t card_addr                    : 32; /**< Data address for media =<2GB is a 32bit byte address and data
04208                                                          address for media > 2GB is a 32bit sector (512B) address.
04209                                                          Hardware advances the card address after each successful block
04210                                                          transfer by 512 for byte addressing and by 1 for sector
04211                                                          addressing. */
04212 #else
04213     uint64_t card_addr                    : 32;
04214     uint64_t block_cnt                    : 16;
04215     uint64_t multi                        : 1;
04216     uint64_t rw                           : 1;
04217     uint64_t rel_wr                       : 1;
04218     uint64_t thres                        : 6;
04219     uint64_t dat_null                     : 1;
04220     uint64_t sector                       : 1;
04221     uint64_t dma_val                      : 1;
04222     uint64_t bus_id                       : 2;
04223     uint64_t reserved_62_63               : 2;
04224 #endif
04225     } cn61xx;
04226     struct cvmx_mio_emm_dma_cn61xx        cn70xx;
04227     struct cvmx_mio_emm_dma_cn61xx        cn70xxp1;
04228     struct cvmx_mio_emm_dma_s             cn73xx;
04229     struct cvmx_mio_emm_dma_s             cn78xx;
04230     struct cvmx_mio_emm_dma_s             cn78xxp1;
04231     struct cvmx_mio_emm_dma_cn61xx        cnf71xx;
04232     struct cvmx_mio_emm_dma_s             cnf75xx;
04233 };

04261 /**

04265  * four-bit operations must be used to access this register. This register is updated by the

04267  */

04274     uint64_t clr                          : 1;  /**< DMA engine abort. When set to 1, DMA is aborted and EN is cleared on completion. */
04275     uint64_t reserved_60_60               : 1;

04280     uint64_t size                         : 20; /**< DMA engine size. Specified in the number of 64-bit transfers (encoded in -1 notation). For
04281                                                          example, to transfer 512 bytes, SIZE = 64 - 1 = 63. */
04282     uint64_t reserved_0_35                : 36;
04283 #else

04289     uint64_t swap32                       : 1;
04290     uint64_t reserved_60_60               : 1;

04294 #endif
04295     } s;

04303 /**

04317 #else
04318     uint64_t reserved_0_2                 : 3;

04321 #endif

04330 /**
04331  * cvmx_mio_emm_dma_fifo_cfg
04332  *
04333  * This register controls DMA FIFO Operations.
04334  *
04335  */
04336 union cvmx_mio_emm_dma_fifo_cfg {
04337     uint64_t u64;
04338     struct cvmx_mio_emm_dma_fifo_cfg_s {
04339 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04340     uint64_t reserved_17_63               : 47;
04341     uint64_t clr                          : 1;  /**< DMA FIFO Clear. When set erases all commands in the DMA FIFO. Must be zero for normal operation. */
04342     uint64_t reserved_13_15               : 3;
04343     uint64_t int_lvl                      : 5;  /**< Interrupt threshold indicating the number of entries remaining in the
04344                                                          DMA FIFO.  An interrupt occurs if the FIFO is read at the level specified.
04345                                                          A value of 0 disables the interrupt.  A value of 17 or greater will cause an
04346                                                          interrupt only if the FIFO is overflowed.
04347                                                          See MIO_EMM_DMA_INT[FIFO]. */
04348     uint64_t reserved_5_7                 : 3;
04349     uint64_t count                        : 5;  /**< Number of entries in the DMA FIFO. This count is incremented by writes to the
04350                                                          MIO_EMM_DMA_FIFO_CMD register and decremented each time the internal DMA engine completes
04351                                                          the previous command successfully.
04352                                                          Up to 16 entries can be placed in the FIFO. Entries written to a full FIFO will
04353                                                          potentially corrupt existing entries.  Care must be taken by software to insure
04354                                                          that this condition does not occur. */
04355 #else
04356     uint64_t count                        : 5;
04357     uint64_t reserved_5_7                 : 3;
04358     uint64_t int_lvl                      : 5;
04359     uint64_t reserved_13_15               : 3;
04360     uint64_t clr                          : 1;
04361     uint64_t reserved_17_63               : 47;
04362 #endif
04363     } s;
04364     struct cvmx_mio_emm_dma_fifo_cfg_s    cn73xx;
04365     struct cvmx_mio_emm_dma_fifo_cfg_s    cn78xx;
04366     struct cvmx_mio_emm_dma_fifo_cfg_s    cn78xxp1;
04367     struct cvmx_mio_emm_dma_fifo_cfg_s    cnf75xx;

04371 /**
04372  * cvmx_mio_emm_dma_fifo_cmd
04373  *
04374  * This register specifies a command that is loaded into the eMMC internal DMA FIFO.  The FIFO is
04375  * used to queue up operations for the MIO_EMM_DMA_CFG/MIO_EMM_DMA_ADR when the DMA completes
04376  * successfully. Writes to this register store both the MIO_EMM_DMA_FIFO_CMD and the
04377  * MIO_EMM_DMA_FIFO_ADR contents into the FIFO and increment the MIO_EMM_DMA_FIFO_CFG[COUNT]
04378  * field.
04379  *
04380  * Note: This register has a similar format to the MIO_EMM_DMA_CFG register with the exception
04381  * that the EN and CLR fields are absent. These are supported in the MIO_EMM_DMA_FIFO_CFG.
04382  */
04383 union cvmx_mio_emm_dma_fifo_cmd {
04384     uint64_t u64;
04385     struct cvmx_mio_emm_dma_fifo_cmd_s {
04386 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04387     uint64_t reserved_63_63               : 1;
04388     uint64_t rw                           : 1;  /**< DMA engine R/W bit: 0 = read, 1 = write. */
04389     uint64_t reserved_61_61               : 1;
04390     uint64_t intdis                       : 1;  /**< DMA command interrupt disable.  When set, the DMA command being submitted will
04391                                                          not generate a MIO_EMM_DMA_INT[DONE] interrupt when it completes.  When cleared
04392                                                          the command will generate the interrupt.
04393                                                          For example, this field can be set for all the DMA commands submitted to the
04394                                                          DMA FIFO in the case of a write to the eMMC device because the MIO_EMM_INT[DONE]
04395                                                          interrupt would signify the end of the operation. It could be cleared on the last
04396                                                          DMA command being submitted to the DMA FIFO and the MIO_EMM_DMA_INT[DONE] would
04397                                                          occur when the read from the eMMC device was available in local memory. */
04398     uint64_t swap32                       : 1;  /**< DMA engine 32-bit swap. */
04399     uint64_t swap16                       : 1;  /**< DMA engine enable 16-bit swap. */
04400     uint64_t swap8                        : 1;  /**< DMA engine enable 8-bit swap. */
04401     uint64_t endian                       : 1;  /**< DMA engine endian mode: 0 = big-endian, 1 = little-endian. */
04402     uint64_t size                         : 20; /**< DMA engine size. Specified in the number of 64-bit transfers (encoded in -1 notation). For
04403                                                          example, to transfer 512 bytes, SIZE = 64 - 1 = 63. */
04404     uint64_t reserved_0_35                : 36;
04405 #else
04406     uint64_t reserved_0_35                : 36;
04407     uint64_t size                         : 20;
04408     uint64_t endian                       : 1;
04409     uint64_t swap8                        : 1;
04410     uint64_t swap16                       : 1;
04411     uint64_t swap32                       : 1;
04412     uint64_t intdis                       : 1;
04413     uint64_t reserved_61_61               : 1;
04414     uint64_t rw                           : 1;
04415     uint64_t reserved_63_63               : 1;
04416 #endif
04417     } s;
04418     struct cvmx_mio_emm_dma_fifo_cmd_s    cn73xx;
04419     struct cvmx_mio_emm_dma_fifo_cmd_s    cn78xx;
04420     struct cvmx_mio_emm_dma_fifo_cmd_cn78xxp1 {
04421 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04422     uint64_t reserved_63_63               : 1;
04423     uint64_t rw                           : 1;  /**< DMA engine R/W bit: 0 = read, 1 = write. */
04424     uint64_t reserved_60_61               : 2;
04425     uint64_t swap32                       : 1;  /**< DMA engine 32-bit swap. */
04426     uint64_t swap16                       : 1;  /**< DMA engine enable 16-bit swap. */
04427     uint64_t swap8                        : 1;  /**< DMA engine enable 8-bit swap. */
04428     uint64_t endian                       : 1;  /**< DMA engine endian mode: 0 = big-endian, 1 = little-endian. */
04429     uint64_t size                         : 20; /**< DMA engine size. Specified in the number of 64-bit transfers (encoded in -1 notation). For
04430                                                          example, to transfer 512 bytes, SIZE = 64 - 1 = 63. */
04431     uint64_t reserved_0_35                : 36;
04432 #else
04433     uint64_t reserved_0_35                : 36;
04434     uint64_t size                         : 20;
04435     uint64_t endian                       : 1;
04436     uint64_t swap8                        : 1;
04437     uint64_t swap16                       : 1;
04438     uint64_t swap32                       : 1;
04439     uint64_t reserved_60_61               : 2;
04440     uint64_t rw                           : 1;
04441     uint64_t reserved_63_63               : 1;
04442 #endif
04443     } cn78xxp1;
04444     struct cvmx_mio_emm_dma_fifo_cmd_s    cnf75xx;
04445 };
04446 typedef union cvmx_mio_emm_dma_fifo_cmd cvmx_mio_emm_dma_fifo_cmd_t;

05018 /**
05019  * cvmx_mio_emm_switch
05020  *
05021  * MIO_EMM_SWITCH = MIO EMMC Operating mode switch Register
05022  *
05023  */
05024 union cvmx_mio_emm_switch {
05025     uint64_t u64;
05026     struct cvmx_mio_emm_switch_s {
05027 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05028     uint64_t reserved_62_63               : 2;
05029     uint64_t bus_id                       : 2;  /**< Specifies the eMMC bus id. */
05030     uint64_t switch_exe                   : 1;  /**< When clear, the operating modes are updated directly without performing any
05031                                                          SWITCH operations. This allows software to perform the SWITCH operations manually, then
05032                                                          update the hardware.
05033                                                          Software writes this bit to a 1 to indicate that hardware should perform the necessary
05034                                                          SWITCH operations.
05035                                                          * First, the POWER_CLASS switch is performed. If it fails, [SWITCH_ERR0] is set and the
05036                                                          remaining SWITCH operations are not performed. If it succeeds, [POWER_CLASS] is
05037                                                          updated and the HS_TIMING switch is performed.
05038                                                          * If the HS_TIMING switch fails, [SWITCH_ERR1] is set and the remaining SWITCH operations
05039                                                          are not performed. If it succeeds, [HS_TIMING] is updated and the BUS_WIDTH switch
05040                                                          operation is performed.
05041                                                          * If the BUS_WIDTH switch operation fails, [SWITCH_ERR2] is set. If it succeeds, the
05042                                                          BUS_WITDH is updated.
05043                                                          Changes to CLK_HI and CLK_LO are discarded if any SWITCH_ERR occurs. */
05044     uint64_t switch_err0                  : 1;  /**< Error encountered while performing POWER_CLASS switch. See MIO_EMM_RSP_STS. */
05045     uint64_t switch_err1                  : 1;  /**< Error encountered while performing HS_TIMING switch. See MIO_EMM_RSP_STS. */
05046     uint64_t switch_err2                  : 1;  /**< Error encountered while performing BUS_WIDTH switch. See MIO_EMM_RSP_STS. */
05047     uint64_t reserved_49_55               : 7;
05048     uint64_t hs_timing                    : 1;  /**< Requested update to HS_TIMING. */
05049     uint64_t reserved_43_47               : 5;
05050     uint64_t bus_width                    : 3;  /**< Requested update to BUS_WIDTH. */
05051     uint64_t reserved_36_39               : 4;
05052     uint64_t power_class                  : 4;  /**< Requested update to POWER_CLASS. */
05053     uint64_t clk_hi                       : 16; /**< Requested update to CLK_HI. */
05054     uint64_t clk_lo                       : 16; /**< Requested update to CLK_LO. */
05055 #else
05056     uint64_t clk_lo                       : 16;
05057     uint64_t clk_hi                       : 16;
05058     uint64_t power_class                  : 4;
05059     uint64_t reserved_36_39               : 4;
05060     uint64_t bus_width                    : 3;
05061     uint64_t reserved_43_47               : 5;
05062     uint64_t hs_timing                    : 1;
05063     uint64_t reserved_49_55               : 7;
05064     uint64_t switch_err2                  : 1;
05065     uint64_t switch_err1                  : 1;
05066     uint64_t switch_err0                  : 1;
05067     uint64_t switch_exe                   : 1;
05068     uint64_t bus_id                       : 2;
05069     uint64_t reserved_62_63               : 2;
05070 #endif
05071     } s;
05072     struct cvmx_mio_emm_switch_s          cn61xx;
05073     struct cvmx_mio_emm_switch_s          cn70xx;
05074     struct cvmx_mio_emm_switch_s          cn70xxp1;
05075     struct cvmx_mio_emm_switch_s          cn73xx;
05076     struct cvmx_mio_emm_switch_s          cn78xx;
05077     struct cvmx_mio_emm_switch_s          cn78xxp1;
05078     struct cvmx_mio_emm_switch_s          cnf71xx;
05079     struct cvmx_mio_emm_switch_s          cnf75xx;
05080 };

05083 /**
05084  * cvmx_mio_emm_wdog
05085  *
05086  * MIO_EMM_WDOG = MIO EMMC Watchdog Register
05087  *
05088  */
05089 union cvmx_mio_emm_wdog {
05090     uint64_t u64;
05091     struct cvmx_mio_emm_wdog_s {
05092 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05093     uint64_t reserved_26_63               : 38;
05094     uint64_t clk_cnt                      : 26; /**< Maximum number of CLK_CNT cycles to wait for the card to return a response, read data, or
05095                                                          the 3-bit CRC status token following write data. The following timeouts are detected:
05096                                                          Expected response to a command doesn't occur causing MIO_EMM_RSP_STS[RSP_TIMEOUT].
05097                                                          On a read command, expected data isn't returned causing MIO_EMM_RSP_STS[BLK_TIMEOUT].
05098                                                          On a multi read command, expected data isn't returned causing
05099                                                          MIO_EMM_RSP_STS[BLK_TIMEOUT].
05100                                                          On a write command, expected token to a write block isn't received causing
05101                                                          MIO_EMM_RSP_STS[BLK_TIMEOUT].
05102                                                          If a stop command is issued by the hardware and no response is returned causing
05103                                                          MIO_EMM_RSP_STS[STP_TIMEOUT].
05104                                                          Issues this timeout doesn't cover are stalls induced by the card which are not limited by
05105                                                          the specifications.
05106                                                          For example, when a write multi command is issued to the card and a block (not the last)
05107                                                          is transferred the card can "stall" the CNXXXX by forcing emmc_data<0> low for as long as
05108                                                          it wants to free up buffer space.
05109                                                          The second case is when the last block of a write or multi write is being transferred and
05110                                                          the card elects to perform some background tasks. The same stall mechanism with
05111                                                          emmc_data<0> is used but this can last for an extend time period. */
05112 #else
05113     uint64_t clk_cnt                      : 26;
05114     uint64_t reserved_26_63               : 38;
05115 #endif
05116     } s;
05117     struct cvmx_mio_emm_wdog_s            cn61xx;
05118     struct cvmx_mio_emm_wdog_s            cn70xx;
05119     struct cvmx_mio_emm_wdog_s            cn70xxp1;
05120     struct cvmx_mio_emm_wdog_s            cn73xx;
05121     struct cvmx_mio_emm_wdog_s            cn78xx;
05122     struct cvmx_mio_emm_wdog_s            cn78xxp1;
05123     struct cvmx_mio_emm_wdog_s            cnf71xx;
05124     struct cvmx_mio_emm_wdog_s            cnf75xx;
05125 };
05126 typedef union cvmx_mio_emm_wdog cvmx_mio_emm_wdog_t;

05249 /**
05250  * cvmx_mio_fus_dat2
05251  *
05252  * Notes:
05253  * CHIP_ID is consumed in several places within Octeon.
05254  *
05255  *    * Core COP0 ProcessorIdentification[Revision]
05256  *    * Core EJTAG DeviceIdentification[Version]
05257  *    * PCI_CFG02[RID]
05258  *    * JTAG controller
05259  *
05260  * Note: The JTAG controller gets CHIP_ID[3:0] solely from the laser fuses.
05261  * Modification to the efuses will not change what the JTAG controller reports
05262  * for CHIP_ID.

05272                                                          0x1 = Emulator.
05273                                                          0x2 = RTL simulator.
05274                                                          0x3 = ASIM.
05275                                                          0x4-0x7 = Reserved. */

05281     uint64_t fus318                       : 1;  /**< Reserved. */
05282     uint64_t raid_en                      : 1;  /**< Fuse information - RAID enabled. */
05283     uint64_t reserved_30_31               : 2;

05285     uint64_t nodfa_cp2                    : 1;  /**< Reserved. */

05288                                                          modes:

05291                                                          _ DORM_CRYPTO = 1, NOCRYPTO = 0 Dormant encryption enable.
05292                                                          _ DORM_CRYPTO = 1, NOCRYPTO = 1 Authentik mode. */

06492 /**
06493  * cvmx_mio_fus_pll
06494  *
06495  * This register contains PLL Status and controls for the MSC_CLKOUT and
06496  * MSC_SYS_CLKOUT pins.  The fields are reset to zero on a cold reset.
06497  * the values are preserved on both a warm and soft reset for pass 2.
06498  */
06499 union cvmx_mio_fus_pll {
06500     uint64_t u64;
06501     struct cvmx_mio_fus_pll_s {
06502 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06503     uint64_t reserved_48_63               : 16;
06504     uint64_t rclk_align_r                 : 8;  /**< RCLK right alignment settings */
06505     uint64_t rclk_align_l                 : 8;  /**< RCLK left alignment settings */
06506     uint64_t reserved_15_31               : 17;
06507     uint64_t core_status                  : 3;  /**< Core-clock PLL status information. */
06508     uint64_t reserved_11_11               : 1;
06509     uint64_t pnr_status                   : 3;  /**< Coprocessor-clock PLL status information. */
06510     uint64_t c_cout_rst                   : 1;  /**< Core clockout postscaler reset. The core clockout postscaler should be placed in reset at
06511                                                          least 10 reference-clock cycles prior to changing C_COUT_SEL. The core clockout postscaler
06512                                                          should remain under reset for at least 10 reference-clock cycles after C_COUT_SEL changes. */
06513     uint64_t c_cout_sel                   : 2;  /**< Core-clock output select:
06514                                                          0x0 = Core clock.
06515                                                          0x1 = PS output.
06516                                                          0x2 = PLL output.
06517                                                          0x3 = Undivided core clock. */
06518     uint64_t pnr_cout_rst                 : 1;  /**< SYS clockout postscaler reset. The PNR clockout postscaler should be placed in reset at
06519                                                          least 10 reference-clock cycles prior to changing PNR_COUT_SEL. The SYS clockout
06520                                                          postscaler
06521                                                          should remain under reset for at least 10 reference-clock cycles after PNR_COUT_SEL
06522                                                          changes. */
06523     uint64_t pnr_cout_sel                 : 2;  /**< Coprocessor-clock output select:
06524                                                          0x0 = Coprocessor clock.
06525                                                          0x1 = PS output.
06526                                                          0x2 = PLL output.
06527                                                          0x3 = Undivided core clock. */
06528     uint64_t rfslip                       : 1;  /**< Reserved */
06529     uint64_t fbslip                       : 1;  /**< Reserved */
06530 #else
06531     uint64_t fbslip                       : 1;
06532     uint64_t rfslip                       : 1;
06533     uint64_t pnr_cout_sel                 : 2;
06534     uint64_t pnr_cout_rst                 : 1;
06535     uint64_t c_cout_sel                   : 2;
06536     uint64_t c_cout_rst                   : 1;
06537     uint64_t pnr_status                   : 3;
06538     uint64_t reserved_11_11               : 1;
06539     uint64_t core_status                  : 3;
06540     uint64_t reserved_15_31               : 17;
06541     uint64_t rclk_align_l                 : 8;
06542     uint64_t rclk_align_r                 : 8;
06543     uint64_t reserved_48_63               : 16;
06544 #endif
06545     } s;
06546     struct cvmx_mio_fus_pll_cn50xx {
06547 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06548     uint64_t reserved_2_63                : 62;
06549     uint64_t rfslip                       : 1;  /**< PLL reference clock slip */
06550     uint64_t fbslip                       : 1;  /**< PLL feedback clock slip */
06551 #else
06552     uint64_t fbslip                       : 1;
06553     uint64_t rfslip                       : 1;
06554     uint64_t reserved_2_63                : 62;
06555 #endif
06556     } cn50xx;
06557     struct cvmx_mio_fus_pll_cn50xx        cn52xx;
06558     struct cvmx_mio_fus_pll_cn50xx        cn52xxp1;
06559     struct cvmx_mio_fus_pll_cn50xx        cn56xx;
06560     struct cvmx_mio_fus_pll_cn50xx        cn56xxp1;
06561     struct cvmx_mio_fus_pll_cn50xx        cn58xx;
06562     struct cvmx_mio_fus_pll_cn50xx        cn58xxp1;
06563     struct cvmx_mio_fus_pll_cn61xx {
06564 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06565     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
06566     uint64_t c_cout_rst                   : 1;  /**< Core clkout postscaler reset */
06567     uint64_t c_cout_sel                   : 2;  /**< Core clkout select
06568                                                          0=RCLK,1=PS output,2=PLL output,3=undivided RCLK |   $PR
06569                                                          (***Pass 1.x: 3=GND) */
06570     uint64_t pnr_cout_rst                 : 1;  /**< PNR  clkout postscaler reset */
06571     uint64_t pnr_cout_sel                 : 2;  /**< PNR  clkout select
06572                                                          0=SCLK,1=PS output,2=PLL output,3=undivided RCLK |   $PR
06573                                                          (***Pass 1.x: 3=GND) */
06574     uint64_t rfslip                       : 1;  /**< Reserved */
06575     uint64_t fbslip                       : 1;  /**< Reserved */
06576 #else
06577     uint64_t fbslip                       : 1;
06578     uint64_t rfslip                       : 1;
06579     uint64_t pnr_cout_sel                 : 2;
06580     uint64_t pnr_cout_rst                 : 1;
06581     uint64_t c_cout_sel                   : 2;
06582     uint64_t c_cout_rst                   : 1;
06583     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
06584 #endif
06585     } cn61xx;
06586     struct cvmx_mio_fus_pll_cn61xx        cn63xx;
06587     struct cvmx_mio_fus_pll_cn61xx        cn63xxp1;
06588     struct cvmx_mio_fus_pll_cn61xx        cn66xx;
06589     struct cvmx_mio_fus_pll_cn68xx {
06590 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06591     uint64_t reserved_48_63               : 16;
06592     uint64_t rclk_align_r                 : 8;  /**< RCLK right alignment settings */
06593     uint64_t rclk_align_l                 : 8;  /**< RCLK left alignment settings */
06594     uint64_t reserved_8_31                : 24;
06595     uint64_t c_cout_rst                   : 1;  /**< Core clkout postscaler reset */
06596     uint64_t c_cout_sel                   : 2;  /**< Core clkout select
06597                                                          0=RCLK,1=PS output,2=PLL output,3=undivided RCLK |   $PR */
06598     uint64_t pnr_cout_rst                 : 1;  /**< PNR  clkout postscaler reset */
06599     uint64_t pnr_cout_sel                 : 2;  /**< PNR  clkout select

06661 /**
06662  * cvmx_mio_fus_prog
06663  *
06664  * DON'T PUT IN HRM*
06665  *
06666  *
06667  * Notes:
06668  * This CSR is not present in the HRM.
06669  *
06670  * To write a bank of fuses, SW must set MIO_FUS_WADR[ADDR] to the bank to be
06671  * programmed and then set each bit within MIO_FUS_BNK_DATX to indicate which
06672  * fuses to blow.  Once ADDR, and DAT are setup, SW can write to
06673  * MIO_FUS_PROG[PROG] to start the bank write and poll on PROG.  Once PROG is
06674  * clear, the bank write is complete.
06675  *
06676  * A soft blow is still subject to lockdown fuses.  After a soft/warm reset, the
06677  * chip will behave as though the fuses were actually blown.  A cold reset restores
06678  * the actual fuse valuse.
06679  */
06680 union cvmx_mio_fus_prog {
06681     uint64_t u64;
06682     struct cvmx_mio_fus_prog_s {
06683 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06684     uint64_t reserved_1_63                : 63;
06685     uint64_t prog                         : 1;  /**< N/A */
06686 #else
06687     uint64_t prog                         : 1;
06688     uint64_t reserved_1_63                : 63;
06689 #endif
06690     } s;
06691     struct cvmx_mio_fus_prog_s            cn30xx;
06692     struct cvmx_mio_fus_prog_s            cn31xx;
06693     struct cvmx_mio_fus_prog_s            cn38xx;
06694     struct cvmx_mio_fus_prog_s            cn38xxp2;
06695     struct cvmx_mio_fus_prog_s            cn50xx;
06696     struct cvmx_mio_fus_prog_s            cn52xx;
06697     struct cvmx_mio_fus_prog_s            cn52xxp1;
06698     struct cvmx_mio_fus_prog_s            cn56xx;
06699     struct cvmx_mio_fus_prog_s            cn56xxp1;
06700     struct cvmx_mio_fus_prog_s            cn58xx;
06701     struct cvmx_mio_fus_prog_s            cn58xxp1;
06702     struct cvmx_mio_fus_prog_cn61xx {
06703 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06704     uint64_t reserved_2_63                : 62;
06705     uint64_t soft                         : 1;  /**< When set with PROG, causes only the local storeage
06706                                                          to change.  Will not really blow any fuses.  HW
06707                                                          will clear when the program operation is complete */
06708     uint64_t prog                         : 1;  /**< Blow the fuse bank
06709                                                          SW will set PROG, and then the HW will clear
06710                                                          when the program operation is complete */
06711 #else
06712     uint64_t prog                         : 1;
06713     uint64_t soft                         : 1;
06714     uint64_t reserved_2_63                : 62;
06715 #endif
06716     } cn61xx;
06717     struct cvmx_mio_fus_prog_cn61xx       cn63xx;
06718     struct cvmx_mio_fus_prog_cn61xx       cn63xxp1;
06719     struct cvmx_mio_fus_prog_cn61xx       cn66xx;
06720     struct cvmx_mio_fus_prog_cn61xx       cn68xx;
06721     struct cvmx_mio_fus_prog_cn61xx       cn68xxp1;
06722     struct cvmx_mio_fus_prog_cn70xx {
06723 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06724     uint64_t reserved_2_63                : 62;
06725     uint64_t sft                          : 1;  /**< N/A */
06726     uint64_t prog                         : 1;  /**< N/A */
06727 #else
06728     uint64_t prog                         : 1;
06729     uint64_t sft                          : 1;
06730     uint64_t reserved_2_63                : 62;
06731 #endif
06732     } cn70xx;

06876 /**
06877  * cvmx_mio_fus_rcmd
06878  *
06879  * To read an efuse, software writes MIO_FUS_RCMD[ADDR,PEND] with the byte address of the fuse in
06880  * question, then software can poll MIO_FUS_RCMD[PEND]. When PEND is clear, then
06881  * MIO_FUS_RCMD[DAT] is valid. In addition, if the efuse read went to the efuse banks (e.g.
06882  * (ADDR/16) not [0,1,7] || EFUSE), software can read MIO_FUS_BNK_DAT() which contains all 128
06883  * fuses in the bank associated in ADDR.  Fuses 1023..960 are not accessible if
06884  * MIO_FUS_DAT2[DORM_CRYPTO] is enabled.
06885  */
06886 union cvmx_mio_fus_rcmd {
06887     uint64_t u64;
06888     struct cvmx_mio_fus_rcmd_s {
06889 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06890     uint64_t reserved_24_63               : 40;
06891     uint64_t dat                          : 8;  /**< 8 bits of fuse data. */
06892     uint64_t reserved_13_15               : 3;
06893     uint64_t pend                         : 1;  /**< Software sets this bit on a write to start FUSE read operation. Hardware clears when read
06894                                                          is complete and the DAT is valid. */
06895     uint64_t reserved_11_11               : 1;
06896     uint64_t addr_hi                      : 2;  /**< Upper fuse address bits to extend space beyond 2k fuses. Valid range is 0x0-0x2. */
06897     uint64_t efuse                        : 1;  /**< When set, return data from the efuse storage rather than the local storage. */
06898     uint64_t addr                         : 8;  /**< The byte address of the fuse to read. */
06899 #else
06900     uint64_t addr                         : 8;
06901     uint64_t efuse                        : 1;
06902     uint64_t addr_hi                      : 2;
06903     uint64_t reserved_11_11               : 1;
06904     uint64_t pend                         : 1;
06905     uint64_t reserved_13_15               : 3;
06906     uint64_t dat                          : 8;
06907     uint64_t reserved_24_63               : 40;
06908 #endif
06909     } s;
06910     struct cvmx_mio_fus_rcmd_cn30xx {
06911 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06912     uint64_t reserved_24_63               : 40;

06916                                                          operation.  HW clears when read is complete and
06917                                                          the DAT is valid */

06981 /**
06982  * cvmx_mio_fus_read_times
06983  *
06984  * IFB fuses are 0 to 1791. The reset values are for IFB fuses for PLL_REF_CLK up to 100MHz when
06985  * core PLL is engaged. If any of the formulas below result in a value less than zero, the
06986  * corresponding timing parameter should be set to zero.
06987  *
06988  * Prior to issuing a read to the fuse banks (via MIO_FUS_RCMD), this register should be written
06989  * with the timing parameters that will be read.
06990  * This register should not be written while MIO_FUS_RCMD[PEND] = 1.
06991  */
06992 union cvmx_mio_fus_read_times {
06993     uint64_t u64;
06994     struct cvmx_mio_fus_read_times_s {
06995 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06996     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
06997     uint64_t done                         : 4;  /**< Hold time of CSB, PGENB, and LOAD with respect to falling edge of STROBE for read and
06998                                                          write mode in PLL_REF_CLK + 1 cycles. Timing specs are th_CS = 6ns, th_PG = 10ns, th_LD_p
06999                                                          = 7ns. Default of 0x0 yields 20ns for a PLL_REF_CLK of 50 MHz, 10ns at 100MHz. */
07000     uint64_t reserved_0_27                : 28;
07001 #else
07002     uint64_t reserved_0_27                : 28;
07003     uint64_t done                         : 4;
07004     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
07005 #endif
07006     } s;
07007     struct cvmx_mio_fus_read_times_cn61xx {
07008 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07009     uint64_t reserved_26_63               : 38;
07010     uint64_t sch                          : 4;  /**< Hold CS for (SCH+1) refclks after FSET desserts
07011 
07012                                                          SCH = (tSCH/refclk period)-1
07013 
07014                                                          For IFB: tSCH = 160ns
07015                                                          For L6G: tSCH =  10ns */
07016     uint64_t fsh                          : 4;  /**< Hold FSET for (FSH+1) refclks after PRCHG deasserts
07017 
07018                                                          FSH = (tFSH/refclk period)-1
07019 
07020                                                          For IFB: tFSH = 160ns
07021                                                          For L6G: tFSH =  10ns */
07022     uint64_t prh                          : 4;  /**< Assert PRCHG (PRH+1) refclks after SIGDEV deasserts
07023 
07024                                                          PRH = (tPRH/refclk period)-1
07025 
07026                                                          For IFB: tPRH =  70ns
07027                                                          For L6G: tPRH =  10ns */
07028     uint64_t sdh                          : 4;  /**< Hold SIGDEV for (SDH+1) refclks after FSET asserts
07029 
07030                                                          SDH = (tSDH/refclk period)-1
07031 
07032                                                          For IFB: tPRH =  10ns
07033                                                          For L6G: tPRH =  10ns */
07034     uint64_t setup                        : 10; /**< Assert CS for (SETUP+1) refclks before asserting
07035                                                          SIGDEV, FSET, or PRCHG
07036 
07037                                                          SETUP=(tRDS/refclk period)-1
07038 
07039                                                          For IFB: tRDS = 10000ns
07040                                                          For L6G: tRDS = max(tSCS,tSDS,tPRS)
07041                                                            where tSCS   = 10ns
07042                                                                  tSDS   = 10ns
07043                                                                  tPRS   = 10ns */
07044 #else
07045     uint64_t setup                        : 10;
07046     uint64_t sdh                          : 4;
07047     uint64_t prh                          : 4;
07048     uint64_t fsh                          : 4;
07049     uint64_t sch                          : 4;
07050     uint64_t reserved_26_63               : 38;
07051 #endif
07052     } cn61xx;
07053     struct cvmx_mio_fus_read_times_cn61xx cn63xx;
07054     struct cvmx_mio_fus_read_times_cn61xx cn63xxp1;
07055     struct cvmx_mio_fus_read_times_cn61xx cn66xx;
07056     struct cvmx_mio_fus_read_times_cn61xx cn68xx;
07057     struct cvmx_mio_fus_read_times_cn61xx cn68xxp1;
07058     struct cvmx_mio_fus_read_times_cn70xx {
07059 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07060     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
07061     uint64_t done                         : 4;  /**< Hold time of CSB, PGENB, and LOAD with respect to falling edge of STROBE for read and
07062                                                          write mode in PLL_REF_CLK + 1 cycles. Timing specs are th_CS = 6ns, th_PG = 10ns, th_LD_p
07063                                                          = 7ns. Default of 0x0 yields 20ns for a PLL_REF_CLK of 50 MHz, 10ns at 100MHz. */
07064     uint64_t ahd                          : 4;  /**< Hold time of A with respect to falling edge of STROBE for read and write modes in
07065                                                          PLL_REF_CLK + 2 cycles. Timing spec of tsu_A_r and tsu_A_p is 3ns min. Default of 0x0
07066                                                          yields 40ns for a PLL_REF_CLK of 50 MHz, 20ns at 100MHz. */
07067     uint64_t wrstb_wh                     : 12; /**< Pulse width high of STROBE in write mode in PLL_REF_CLK + 1 cycles. Timing spec of
07068                                                          twh_SB_p is 9.8us max. Default of 0x1F3 yields 10 us at PLL_REF_CLK of 50 MHz. */
07069     uint64_t rdstb_wh                     : 4;  /**< Pulse width high of STROBE in read mode in PLL_REF_CLK + 1 cycles. Timing spec of twh_SB_p
07070                                                          is 20ns min. Default of 0x1 yields 40 ns at PLL_REF_CLK of 50 MHz, 20ns at 100MHz. */
07071     uint64_t asu                          : 4;  /**< Setup time of A to rising edge of STROBE for read and write modes in PLL_REF_CLK cycles.
07072                                                          Timing spec of tsu_A_r and tsu_A_p is 12 ns min. Default of 0x1 yields 40 ns at
07073                                                          PLL_REF_CLK of 50 MHz, 20ns at 100MHz. */
07074     uint64_t setup                        : 4;  /**< Setup of CSB, PGENB, LOAD to rising edge of STROBE in read and write modes in PLL_REF_CLK
07075                                                          + 1 cycles. tsu_CS = 16ns, tsu_PG = 14ns, tsu_LD_r = 10ns. Default of 0x0 yields 20 ns
07076                                                          plus ASU cycles at PLL_REF_CLK of 50 MHz, 10ns + ASU at 100MHz. */
07077 #else
07078     uint64_t setup                        : 4;
07079     uint64_t asu                          : 4;
07080     uint64_t rdstb_wh                     : 4;
07081     uint64_t wrstb_wh                     : 12;
07082     uint64_t ahd                          : 4;
07083     uint64_t done                         : 4;
07084     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
07085 #endif
07086     } cn70xx;
07087     struct cvmx_mio_fus_read_times_cn70xx cn70xxp1;
07088     struct cvmx_mio_fus_read_times_cn70xx cn73xx;
07089     struct cvmx_mio_fus_read_times_cn70xx cn78xx;
07090     struct cvmx_mio_fus_read_times_cn70xx cn78xxp1;
07091     struct cvmx_mio_fus_read_times_cn61xx cnf71xx;
07092     struct cvmx_mio_fus_read_times_cn70xx cnf75xx;
07093 };

07308 /**
07309  * cvmx_mio_fus_tgg
07310  *
07311  * This register exists to support Authentik. Authentik code should read this register, then
07312  * clear VAL to prevent other software from observing the value of the TGG fuses.
07313  */
07314 union cvmx_mio_fus_tgg {
07315     uint64_t u64;
07316     struct cvmx_mio_fus_tgg_s {
07317 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07318     uint64_t val                          : 1;  /**< Software may write VAL to zero, but cannot write VAL to a one. When VAL is a 1, DAT reads
07319                                                          the corresponding TGG fuses. When VAL is a zero, DAT reads as zeros. The reset value of
07320                                                          this VAL bit is normally its fuse setting (i.e. TGG<63>). */
07321     uint64_t dat                          : 63; /**< When VAL is clear, DAT will always read as zero, regardless of the value of the TGG<62:0>
07322                                                          fuses. When VAL is set, DAT will return the value of the TGG<62:0> fuses. */
07323 #else
07324     uint64_t dat                          : 63;
07325     uint64_t val                          : 1;
07326 #endif
07327     } s;
07328     struct cvmx_mio_fus_tgg_s             cn61xx;
07329     struct cvmx_mio_fus_tgg_s             cn66xx;
07330     struct cvmx_mio_fus_tgg_s             cn70xx;
07331     struct cvmx_mio_fus_tgg_s             cn70xxp1;
07332     struct cvmx_mio_fus_tgg_s             cn73xx;
07333     struct cvmx_mio_fus_tgg_s             cn78xx;
07334     struct cvmx_mio_fus_tgg_s             cn78xxp1;
07335     struct cvmx_mio_fus_tgg_s             cnf71xx;
07336     struct cvmx_mio_fus_tgg_s             cnf75xx;
07337 };

07688 
07689 /**
07690  * cvmx_mio_ptp_ckout_thresh_hi
07691  *
07692  * This register contains the high bytes of the PTP CKOUT threshold.
07693  * Writes to MIO_PTP_CKOUT_THRESH_HI also clear MIO_PTP_CKOUT_THRESH_LO; in order to update all
07694  * 96 bits, writes MIO_PTP_CKOUT_THRESH_HI followed by MIO_PTP_CKOUT_THRESH_LO.
07695  * This threshold [MIO_PTP_CKOUT_THRESH_HI,  MIO_PTP_CKOUT_THRESH_LO] is a rolling threshold that
07696  * will be updated by hardware:
07697  *   When current PTP_CKOUT before inversion (defined by MIO_PTP_CLOCK_CFG[CKOUT_INV]) is zero,
07698  *   and [MIO_PTP_CLOCK_HI/LO] >= [MIO_PTP_CKOUT_THRESH_HI/LO], the pre-inverted PTP_CKOUT will
07699  *   update to one, and [MIO_PTP_CKOUT_THRESH_HI/LO] will increment by MIO_PTP_CKOUT_HI_INCR.
07700  *   When current PTP_CKOUT before inversion (defined by MIO_PTP_CLOCK_CFG[CKOUT_INV]) is one,
07701  *   and [MIO_PTP_CLOCK_HI/LO] >= [MIO_PTP_CKOUT_THRESH_HI/LO], the pre-inverted PTP_CKOUT will
07702  *   update to zero, and [MIO_PTP_CKOUT_THRESH_HI/LO] will increment by MIO_PTP_CKOUT_LO_INCR.
07703  */
07704 union cvmx_mio_ptp_ckout_thresh_hi {
07705     uint64_t u64;
07706     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_ckout_thresh_hi_s {
07707 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07708     uint64_t nanosec                      : 64; /**< Nanoseconds. */
07709 #else
07710     uint64_t nanosec                      : 64;
07711 #endif
07712     } s;
07713     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_ckout_thresh_hi_s cn61xx;
07714     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_ckout_thresh_hi_s cn66xx;
07715     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_ckout_thresh_hi_s cn68xx;
07716     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_ckout_thresh_hi_s cn70xx;
07717     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_ckout_thresh_hi_s cn70xxp1;
07718     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_ckout_thresh_hi_s cn73xx;
07719     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_ckout_thresh_hi_s cn78xx;
07720     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_ckout_thresh_hi_s cn78xxp1;
07721     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_ckout_thresh_hi_s cnf71xx;
07722     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_ckout_thresh_hi_s cnf75xx;
07723 };
07724 typedef union cvmx_mio_ptp_ckout_thresh_hi cvmx_mio_ptp_ckout_thresh_hi_t;

07756 /**
07757  * cvmx_mio_ptp_clock_cfg
07758  *
07759  * This register configures the timestamp architecture.
07760  *
07761  */
07762 union cvmx_mio_ptp_clock_cfg {

07768                                                          0x0 = Rising edge.

07770                                                          0x2 = Both rising and falling edge.
07771                                                          0x3 = Reserved. */
07772     uint64_t ckout_out4                   : 1;  /**< Destination for PTP Clock Out output
07773                                                          See CKOUT_OUT */
07774     uint64_t pps_out                      : 5;  /**< Destination for PTP PPS output to GPIO
07775                                                          0-19 : GPIO[PPS_OUT[4:0]]
07776                                                          - 20:30: Reserved
07777                                                          31   : Disabled
07778                                                          This should be different from CKOUT_OUT */

07780                                                          0 = Don't invert.
07781                                                          1 = Invert. */
07782     uint64_t pps_en                       : 1;  /**< Enable PTP PPS. (For output pin selection see GPIO_BIT_CFG().) */
07783     uint64_t ckout_out                    : 4;  /**< Destination for PTP Clock Out output to GPIO
07784                                                          0-19 : GPIO[[CKOUT_OUT4,CKOUT_OUT[3:0]]]
07785                                                          - 20:30: Reserved
07786                                                          31   : Disabled
07787                                                          This should be different from PPS_OUT */
07788     uint64_t ckout_inv                    : 1;  /**< Invert PTP CKOUT.
07789                                                          0 = Don't invert.
07790                                                          1 = Invert. */
07791     uint64_t ckout_en                     : 1;  /**< Enable PTP CKOUT. (For output pin selection see GPIO_BIT_CFG().) */
07792     uint64_t evcnt_in                     : 6;  /**< Source for event counter input:
07793                                                          Enumerated by MIO_PTP_EXT_SEL_E. */
