07797                                                          Enumerated by MIO_PTP_EXT_SEL_E. */
07798     uint64_t tstmp_edge                   : 1;  /**< External timestamp input edge: 0 = falling edge, 1 = rising edge. */
07799     uint64_t tstmp_en                     : 1;  /**< Enable external timestamp. */
07800     uint64_t ext_clk_in                   : 6;  /**< Source for external clock when [EXT_CLK_EN] is set:
07801                                                          Enumerated by MIO_PTP_EXT_SEL_E. */
07802     uint64_t ext_clk_en                   : 1;  /**< Use external clock for PTP clock. */
07803     uint64_t ptp_en                       : 1;  /**< Enable PTP module. */
07804 #else
07805     uint64_t ptp_en                       : 1;
07806     uint64_t ext_clk_en                   : 1;
07807     uint64_t ext_clk_in                   : 6;
07808     uint64_t tstmp_en                     : 1;
07809     uint64_t tstmp_edge                   : 1;
07810     uint64_t tstmp_in                     : 6;
07811     uint64_t evcnt_en                     : 1;
07812     uint64_t evcnt_edge                   : 1;
07813     uint64_t evcnt_in                     : 6;
07814     uint64_t ckout_en                     : 1;
07815     uint64_t ckout_inv                    : 1;
07816     uint64_t ckout_out                    : 4;
07817     uint64_t pps_en                       : 1;
07818     uint64_t pps_inv                      : 1;
07819     uint64_t pps_out                      : 5;
07820     uint64_t ckout_out4                   : 1;
07821     uint64_t ext_clk_edge                 : 2;
07822     uint64_t reserved_40_63               : 24;
07823 #endif
07824     } s;
07825     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_clock_cfg_cn61xx {
07826 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07827     uint64_t reserved_42_63               : 22;
07828     uint64_t pps                          : 1;  /**< PTP PPS Output
07829                                                          reflects ptp__pps after PPS_INV inverter */
07830     uint64_t ckout                        : 1;  /**< PTP Clock Output
07831                                                          reflects ptp__ckout after CKOUT_INV inverter */
07832     uint64_t ext_clk_edge                 : 2;  /**< External Clock input edge
07833                                                          00 = rising edge
07834                                                          01 = falling edge
07835                                                          10 = both rising & falling edge
07836                                                          11 = reserved */
07837     uint64_t ckout_out4                   : 1;  /**< Destination for PTP Clock Out output
07838                                                          0-19 : GPIO[[CKOUT_OUT4,CKOUT_OUT[3:0]]]
07839                                                          This should be different from PPS_OUT */
07840     uint64_t pps_out                      : 5;  /**< Destination for PTP PPS output
07841                                                          0-19 : GPIO[PPS_OUT[4:0]]
07842                                                          This should be different from CKOUT_OUT */
07843     uint64_t pps_inv                      : 1;  /**< Invert PTP PPS
07844                                                          0 = don't invert
07845                                                          1 = invert */
07846     uint64_t pps_en                       : 1;  /**< Enable PTP PPS */
07847     uint64_t ckout_out                    : 4;  /**< Destination for PTP Clock Out output
07848                                                          0-19 : GPIO[[CKOUT_OUT4,CKOUT_OUT[3:0]]]
07849                                                          This should be different from PPS_OUT */
07850     uint64_t ckout_inv                    : 1;  /**< Invert PTP Clock Out
07851                                                          0 = don't invert
07852                                                          1 = invert */
07853     uint64_t ckout_en                     : 1;  /**< Enable PTP Clock Out */
07854     uint64_t evcnt_in                     : 6;  /**< Source for event counter input
07855                                                          0x00-0x0f : GPIO[EVCNT_IN[3:0]]
07856                                                          0x20      : GPIO[16]
07857                                                          0x21      : GPIO[17]
07858                                                          0x22      : GPIO[18]
07859                                                          0x23      : GPIO[19]
07860                                                          0x10      : QLM0_REF_CLK
07861                                                          0x11      : QLM1_REF_CLK
07862                                                          0x12      : QLM2_REF_CLK
07863                                                          0x13-0x1f : Reserved
07864                                                          0x24-0x3f : Reserved */
07865     uint64_t evcnt_edge                   : 1;  /**< Event counter input edge

08410 /**
08411  * cvmx_mio_ptp_pps_thresh_hi
08412  *
08413  * This register contains the high bytes of the PTP PPS threshold.
08414  * Writes to MIO_PTP_PPS_THRESH_HI also clear MIO_PTP_PPS_THRESH_LO; in order to update all 96
08415  * bits, writes MIO_PTP_PPS_THRESH_HI followed by MIO_PTP_PPS_THRESH_LO.
08416  * This threshold [MIO_PTP_PPS_THRESH_HI,  MIO_PTP_PPS_THRESH_LO]  is a rolling threshold that
08417  * will be updated by hardware:
08418  *   When current PTP_PPS before inversion (defined by MIO_PTP_CLOCK_CFG[PPS_INV]) is zero,
08419  *   and [MIO_PTP_CLOCK_HI/LO] >=  [MIO_PTP_PPS_THRESH_HI/LO], the pre-inverted PTP_PPS will
08420  *   update to one, and [MIO_PTP_PPS_THRESH_HI/LO] will increment by MIO_PTP_PPS_HI_INCR.
08421  *   When current PTP_PPS before inversion (defined by MIO_PTP_CLOCK_CFG[PPS_INV]) is one,
08422  *   and [MIO_PTP_CLOCK_HI/LO] >=  [MIO_PTP_PPS_THRESH_HI/LO], the pre-inverted PTP_PPS will
08423  *   update to zero, and [MIO_PTP_PPS_THRESH_HI/LO] will increment by MIO_PTP_PPS_LO_INCR.
08424  */
08425 union cvmx_mio_ptp_pps_thresh_hi {
08426     uint64_t u64;
08427     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_pps_thresh_hi_s {
08428 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
08429     uint64_t nanosec                      : 64; /**< Nanoseconds. */
08430 #else
08431     uint64_t nanosec                      : 64;
08432 #endif
08433     } s;
08434     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_pps_thresh_hi_s   cn61xx;
08435     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_pps_thresh_hi_s   cn66xx;
08436     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_pps_thresh_hi_s   cn68xx;
08437     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_pps_thresh_hi_s   cn70xx;
08438     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_pps_thresh_hi_s   cn70xxp1;
08439     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_pps_thresh_hi_s   cn73xx;
08440     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_pps_thresh_hi_s   cn78xx;
08441     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_pps_thresh_hi_s   cn78xxp1;
08442     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_pps_thresh_hi_s   cnf71xx;
08443     struct cvmx_mio_ptp_pps_thresh_hi_s   cnf75xx;
08444 };
08445 typedef union cvmx_mio_ptp_pps_thresh_hi cvmx_mio_ptp_pps_thresh_hi_t;
08446

08706     uint64_t reserved_3_7                 : 5;
08707     uint64_t qlm_cfg                      : 3;  /**< QLM configuration mode
08708                                                             000 = PCIE
08709                                                             001 = ILK
08710                                                             010 = SGMII
08711                                                             011 = XAUI
08712                                                             100 = RESERVED
08713                                                             101 = RESERVED
08714                                                             110 = RESERVED
08715                                                             111 = RXAUI
08716                                                          NOTE: Internal encodings differ from QLM_MODE
08717                                                                pins encodings */
08718 #else
08719     uint64_t qlm_cfg                      : 3;
08720     uint64_t reserved_3_7                 : 5;
08721     uint64_t qlm_spd                      : 4;
08722     uint64_t reserved_12_63               : 52;
08723 #endif
08724     } cn68xx;
08725     struct cvmx_mio_qlmx_cfg_cn68xx       cn68xxp1;
08726     struct cvmx_mio_qlmx_cfg_cn61xx       cnf71xx;
08727 };
08728 typedef union cvmx_mio_qlmx_cfg cvmx_mio_qlmx_cfg_t;
08729 
08730 /**
08731  * cvmx_mio_rst_boot
08732  *
08733  * Notes:
08734  * JTCSRDIS, EJTAGDIS, ROMEN reset to 1 in authentik mode; in all other modes they reset to 0.
08735  *
08736  */
08737 union cvmx_mio_rst_boot {
08738     uint64_t u64;
08739     struct cvmx_mio_rst_boot_s {
08740 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
08741     uint64_t chipkill                     : 1;  /**< A 0->1 transition of CHIPKILL starts the CHIPKILL
08742                                                          timer.  When CHIPKILL=1 and the timer expires,
08743                                                          internal chip reset is asserted forever until the
08744                                                          next chip reset.  The CHIPKILL timer can be
08745                                                          stopped only by a chip (cold, warm, soft) reset.
08746                                                          The length of the CHIPKILL timer is specified by
08747                                                          MIO_RST_CKILL[TIMER]. */
08748     uint64_t jtcsrdis                     : 1;  /**< If JTCSRDIS=1, internal CSR access via JTAG TAP
08749                                                          controller is disabled
08750                                                          This field resets to 1 in Authentik mode, else 0. */
08751     uint64_t ejtagdis                     : 1;  /**< If EJTAGDIS=1, external EJTAG access is disabled
08752                                                          This field resets to 1 in Authentik mode, else 0. */
08753     uint64_t romen                        : 1;  /**< If ROMEN=1, Authentik/eMMC boot ROM is visible
08754                                                          in the boot bus address space.
08755                                                          This field resets to 1 in an Authentik part or
08756                                                          when booting from eMMC. Else, resets to 0. */
08757     uint64_t ckill_ppdis                  : 1;  /**< If CK_PPDIS=1, PPs other than 0 are disabled
08758                                                          during a CHIPKILL.  Writes have no effect when
08759                                                          MIO_RST_BOOT[CHIPKILL]=1. */
08760     uint64_t jt_tstmode                   : 1;  /**< JTAG test mode */
08761     uint64_t reserved_50_57               : 8;
08762     uint64_t lboot_ext                    : 2;  /**< Reserved */
08763     uint64_t reserved_44_47               : 4;
08764     uint64_t qlm4_spd                     : 4;  /**< QLM4_SPD pins sampled at DCOK assertion */
08765     uint64_t qlm3_spd                     : 4;  /**< QLM3_SPD pins sampled at DCOK assertion */
08766     uint64_t c_mul                        : 6;  /**< Core clock multiplier:
08767                                                            C_MUL = (core clk speed) / (ref clock speed)
08768                                                          "ref clock speed" should always be 50MHz.
08769                                                          If PLL_QLM_REF_CLK_EN=0, "ref clock" comes
08770                                                               from PLL_REF_CLK pin.
08771                                                          If PLL_QLM_REF_CLK_EN=1, "ref clock" is
08772                                                               1/2 speed of QLMC_REF_CLK_* pins. */
08773     uint64_t pnr_mul                      : 6;  /**< Coprocessor clock multiplier:
08774                                                            PNR_MUL = (coprocessor clk speed) /
08775                                                                            (ref clock speed)
08776                                                          See C_MUL comments about ref clock. */
08777     uint64_t qlm2_spd                     : 4;  /**< QLM2_SPD, report MIO_QLM2_CFG[SPD] */
08778     uint64_t qlm1_spd                     : 4;  /**< QLM1_SPD, report MIO_QLM1_CFG[SPD] */
08779     uint64_t qlm0_spd                     : 4;  /**< QLM0_SPD, report MIO_QLM0_CFG[SPD] */
08780     uint64_t lboot                        : 10; /**< Last boot cause mask, resets only with dcok.
08781 
08782                                                          bit9 - Soft reset due to watchdog
08783                                                          bit8 - Soft reset due to CIU_SOFT_RST write
08784                                                          bit7 - Warm reset due to cntl0 link-down or
08785                                                                 hot-reset
08786                                                          bit6 - Warm reset due to cntl1 link-down or
08787                                                                 hot-reset
08788                                                          bit5 - Cntl1 reset due to PERST1_L pin
08789                                                          bit4 - Cntl0 reset due to PERST0_L pin
08790                                                          bit3 - Warm reset due to PERST1_L pin
08791                                                          bit2 - Warm reset due to PERST0_L pin
08792                                                          bit1 - Warm reset due to CHIP_RESET_L pin
08793                                                          bit0 - Cold reset due to DCOK pin */
08794     uint64_t rboot                        : 1;  /**< Determines whether core 0 remains in reset after
08795                                                          after chip cold/warm/soft reset. */
08796     uint64_t rboot_pin                    : 1;  /**< Read-only access to REMOTE_BOOT pin */
08797 #else
08798     uint64_t rboot_pin                    : 1;
08799     uint64_t rboot                        : 1;
08800     uint64_t lboot                        : 10;
08801     uint64_t qlm0_spd                     : 4;
08802     uint64_t qlm1_spd                     : 4;
08803     uint64_t qlm2_spd                     : 4;
08804     uint64_t pnr_mul                      : 6;
08805     uint64_t c_mul                        : 6;
08806     uint64_t qlm3_spd                     : 4;
08807     uint64_t qlm4_spd                     : 4;
08808     uint64_t reserved_44_47               : 4;
08809     uint64_t lboot_ext                    : 2;
08810     uint64_t reserved_50_57               : 8;
08811     uint64_t jt_tstmode                   : 1;
08812     uint64_t ckill_ppdis                  : 1;
08813     uint64_t romen                        : 1;
08814     uint64_t ejtagdis                     : 1;
08815     uint64_t jtcsrdis                     : 1;
08816     uint64_t chipkill                     : 1;
08817 #endif
08818     } s;

09242 /**
09243  * cvmx_mio_rst_cntl#
09244  *
09245  * Notes:
09246  * GEN1_Only mode is enabled for PEM0 when QLM1_SPD[0] is set or when sclk < 550Mhz.
09247  * GEN1_Only mode is enabled for PEM1 when QLM1_SPD[1] is set or when sclk < 550Mhz.
09248  */
09249 union cvmx_mio_rst_cntlx {
09250     uint64_t u64;
09251     struct cvmx_mio_rst_cntlx_s {
09252 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
09253     uint64_t reserved_13_63               : 51;
09254     uint64_t in_rev_ln                    : 1;  /**< RO access to corresponding pin PCIE*_REV_LANES
09255                                                          which is used for initial value for REV_LANES
09256                                                          For INT0/CNTL0: pin PCIE0_REV_LANES
09257                                                          For INT1/CNTL1: always zero as no PCIE1 pin */
09258     uint64_t rev_lanes                    : 1;  /**< Reverse the lanes for INT*.
09259                                                          A warm/soft reset will not change this field.
09260                                                          On cold reset, this field is initialized to
09261                                                          IN_REVLANE value.
09262                                                          When QLM1_CFG=1, INT0(PEM0) REV_LANES internal
09263                                                          setting will be always forced to '0', INT1(PEM1)
09264                                                          will be forced to '1' regardless CSR value. */
09265     uint64_t gen1_only                    : 1;  /**< Disable PCIE GEN2 Capability.  This bit is
09266                                                          always unpredictable whenever the controller
09267                                                          is not attached to any SerDes lanes, and is
09268                                                          otherwise always set when SCLK is slower than
09269                                                          550Mhz.
09270                                                          The MIO_RST_CNTL*[GEN1_ONLY] value is based on
09271                                                          the MIO_QLM1_CFG[QLM_SPD] value. */
09272     uint64_t prst_link                    : 1;  /**< Controls whether corresponding controller
09273                                                          link-down or hot-reset causes the assertion of
09274                                                          CIU_SOFT_PRST*[SOFT_PRST]
09275 
09276                                                          A warm/soft reset will not change this field.
09277                                                          On cold reset, this field is initialized to 0 */
09278     uint64_t rst_done                     : 1;  /**< Read-only access to controller reset status
09279 
09280                                                          RESET_DONE is always zero (i.e. the controller
09281                                                          is held in reset) when:
09282                                                            - CIU_SOFT_PRST*[SOFT_PRST]=1, or
09283                                                            - RST_RCV==1 and PERST*_L pin is asserted */
09284     uint64_t rst_link                     : 1;  /**< Controls whether corresponding controller
09285                                                          link-down or hot-reset causes a warm chip reset
09286                                                          On cold reset, this field is initialized as
09287                                                          follows:
09288                                                             0 = when corresponding HOST_MODE=1
09289                                                             1 = when corresponding HOST_MODE=0
09290 
09291                                                          Note that a link-down or hot-reset event can
09292                                                          never cause a warm chip reset when the
09293                                                          controller is in reset (i.e. can never cause a
09294                                                          warm reset when RST_DONE==0). */
09295     uint64_t host_mode                    : 1;  /**< RO access to corresponding strap PCIE*_HOST_MODE
09296                                                          For CNTL1/INT1, HOST_MODE is always '1' because
09297                                                          there is no PCIE1_HOST_MODE pin. */
09298     uint64_t prtmode                      : 2;  /**< Port mode
09299                                                             0 = port is EP mode
09300                                                             1 = port is RC mode
09301                                                             2,3 = Reserved
09302                                                          A warm/soft reset will not change this field.
09303                                                          On cold reset, this field is initialized as
09304                                                          HOST_MODE (corresponding strap PCIE*_HOST_MODE) */
09305     uint64_t rst_drv                      : 1;  /**< Controls whether corresponding PERST*_L chip pin
09306                                                          is driven by the OCTEON.  A warm/soft reset
09307                                                          will not change this field.  On cold reset,
09308                                                          this field is initialized as follows:
09309                                                           0 = when corresponding HOST_MODE=0
09310                                                           1 = when corresponding HOST_MODE=1
09311 
09312                                                          When set, OCTEON drives the corresponding
09313                                                          PERST*_L pin. Otherwise, OCTEON does not drive
09314                                                          the corresponding PERST*_L pin. */
09315     uint64_t rst_rcv                      : 1;  /**< Controls whether corresponding PERST*_L chip pin
09316                                                          is recieved by OCTEON.  A warm/soft reset
09317                                                          will not change this field.  On cold reset,
09318                                                          this field is initialized as follows:
09319                                                           0 = when corresponding HOST_MODE=1
09320                                                           1 = when corresponding HOST_MODE=0
09321 
09322                                                          When RST_RCV==1, the PERST*_L value is
09323                                                          received and may be used to reset the
09324                                                          controller and (optionally, based on RST_CHIP)
09325                                                          warm reset the chip.
09326 
09327                                                          When RST_RCV==1 (and RST_CHIP=0),
09328                                                          MIO_RST_INT[PERST*] gets set when the PERST*_L
09329                                                          pin asserts. (This interrupt can alert SW
09330                                                          whenever the external reset pin initiates a
09331                                                          controller reset sequence.)
09332 
09333                                                          RST_VAL gives the PERST*_L pin value when
09334                                                          RST_RCV==1.
09335 
09336                                                          When RST_RCV==0, the PERST*_L pin value is
09337                                                          ignored. */
09338     uint64_t rst_chip                     : 1;  /**< Controls whether corresponding PERST*_L chip
09339                                                          pin causes a chip warm reset like CHIP_RESET_L.
09340                                                          A warm/soft reset will not change this field.
09341                                                          On cold reset, this field is initialized to 0.
09342 
09343                                                          RST_CHIP is not used when RST_RCV==0.
09344 
09345                                                          When RST_RCV==0, RST_CHIP is ignored.
09346 
09347                                                          When RST_RCV==1, RST_CHIP==1, and PERST*_L
09348                                                          asserts, a chip warm reset will be generated. */
09349     uint64_t rst_val                      : 1;  /**< Read-only access to corresponding PERST*_L pin
09350                                                          Unpredictable when RST_RCV==0. Reads as 1 when
09351                                                          RST_RCV==1 and the PERST*_L pin is asserted.
09352                                                          Reads as 0 when RST_RCV==1 and the PERST*_L
09353                                                          pin is not asserted. */
09354 #else
09355     uint64_t rst_val                      : 1;
09356     uint64_t rst_chip                     : 1;
09357     uint64_t rst_rcv                      : 1;
09358     uint64_t rst_drv                      : 1;
09359     uint64_t prtmode                      : 2;
09360     uint64_t host_mode                    : 1;
09361     uint64_t rst_link                     : 1;
09362     uint64_t rst_done                     : 1;
09363     uint64_t prst_link                    : 1;
09364     uint64_t gen1_only                    : 1;
09365     uint64_t rev_lanes                    : 1;
09366     uint64_t in_rev_ln                    : 1;
09367     uint64_t reserved_13_63               : 51;
09368 #endif
09369     } s;
09370     struct cvmx_mio_rst_cntlx_s           cn61xx;
09371     struct cvmx_mio_rst_cntlx_cn66xx {
09372 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
09373     uint64_t reserved_10_63               : 54;
09374     uint64_t prst_link                    : 1;  /**< Controls whether corresponding controller
09375                                                          link-down or hot-reset causes the assertion of
09376                                                          CIU_SOFT_PRST*[SOFT_PRST]
09377 
09378                                                          A warm/soft reset will not change this field.
09379                                                          On cold reset, this field is initialized to 0 */
09380     uint64_t rst_done                     : 1;  /**< Read-only access to controller reset status
09381 
09382                                                          RESET_DONE is always zero (i.e. the controller
09383                                                          is held in reset) when:
09384                                                            - CIU_SOFT_PRST*[SOFT_PRST]=1, or
09385                                                            - RST_RCV==1 and PERST*_L pin is asserted */
09386     uint64_t rst_link                     : 1;  /**< Controls whether corresponding controller
09387                                                          link-down or hot-reset causes a warm chip reset
09388                                                          On cold reset, this field is initialized as
09389                                                          follows:
09390                                                             0 = when corresponding strap QLM*_HOST_MODE=1
09391                                                             1 = when corresponding strap QLM*_HOST_MODE=0
09392 
09393                                                          For MIO_RST_CNTL2 and MIO_RST_CNTL3, this field
09394                                                          is initialized to 1 on cold reset.
09395 
09396                                                          Note that a link-down or hot-reset event can
09397                                                          never cause a warm chip reset when the
09398                                                          controller is in reset (i.e. can never cause a
09399                                                          warm reset when RST_DONE==0). */
09400     uint64_t host_mode                    : 1;  /**< RO access to corresponding strap QLM*_HOST_MODE
09401 
09402                                                          For MIO_RST_CNTL2 and MIO_RST_CNTL3, this field
09403                                                          is reserved/RAZ.
09404 
09405                                                          QLM0_HOST_MODE corresponds to PCIe0/sRIO0
09406                                                          QLM1_HOST_MODE corresponds to PCIe1/sRIO1 */
09407     uint64_t prtmode                      : 2;  /**< Port mode
09408                                                             0 = port is EP mode
09409                                                             1 = port is RC mode
09410                                                             2,3 = Reserved
09411                                                          A warm/soft reset will not change this field.
09412                                                          On cold reset, this field is initialized as
09413                                                          follows:
09414                                                             0 = when corresponding strap QLM*_HOST_MODE=0
09415                                                             1 = when corresponding strap QLM*_HOST_MODE=1
09416 
09417                                                          For MIO_RST_CNTL2 and MIO_RST_CNTL3, this field
09418                                                          is initialized to 0 on cold reset. */
09419     uint64_t rst_drv                      : 1;  /**< Controls whether corresponding PERST*_L chip pin
09420                                                            is driven by the OCTEON.  A warm/soft reset
09421                                                            will not change this field.  On cold reset,
09422                                                            this field is initialized as follows:
09423                                                             0 = when corresponding strap QLM*_HOST_MODE=0
09424                                                             1 = when corresponding strap QLM*_HOST_MODE=1
09425 
09426                                                            When set, OCTEON drives the corresponding
09427                                                            PERST*_L pin. Otherwise, OCTEON does not drive
09428                                                            the corresponding PERST*_L pin.
09429 
09430                                                          For MIO_RST_CNTL2 and MIO_RST_CNTL3, this field
09431                                                          is reserved/RAZ. */
09432     uint64_t rst_rcv                      : 1;  /**< Controls whether corresponding PERST*_L chip pin
09433                                                            is recieved by OCTEON.  A warm/soft reset
09434                                                            will not change this field.  On cold reset,
09435                                                            this field is initialized as follows:
09436                                                             0 = when corresponding strap QLM*_HOST_MODE=1
09437                                                             1 = when corresponding strap QLM*_HOST_MODE=0
09438

09440                                                            received and may be used to reset the
09441                                                            controller and (optionally, based on RST_CHIP)

09569                                                          PERST*_L pin. Otherwise, OCTEON does not drive
09570                                                          the corresponding PERST*_L pin. */
09571     uint64_t rst_rcv                      : 1;  /**< Controls whether corresponding PERST*_L chip pin
09572                                                          is recieved by OCTEON.  A warm/soft reset
09573                                                          will not change this field.  On cold reset,
09574                                                          this field is initialized as follows:
09575                                                           0 = when corresponding HOST_MODE=1
09576                                                           1 = when corresponding HOST_MODE=0
09577 
09578                                                          When RST_RCV==1, the PERST*_L value is
09579                                                          received and may be used to reset the
09580                                                          controller and (optionally, based on RST_CHIP)
09581                                                          warm reset the chip.
09582 
09583                                                          When RST_RCV==1 (and RST_CHIP=0),
09584                                                          MIO_RST_INT[PERST*] gets set when the PERST*_L
09585                                                          pin asserts. (This interrupt can alert SW
09586                                                          whenever the external reset pin initiates a
09587                                                          controller reset sequence.)
09588 
09589                                                          RST_VAL gives the PERST*_L pin value when
09590                                                          RST_RCV==1.
09591 
09592                                                          When RST_RCV==0, the PERST*_L pin value is
09593                                                          ignored. */
09594     uint64_t rst_chip                     : 1;  /**< Controls whether corresponding PERST*_L chip
09595                                                          pin causes a chip warm reset like CHIP_RESET_L.
09596                                                          A warm/soft reset will not change this field.
09597                                                          On cold reset, this field is initialized to 0.
09598 
09599                                                          RST_CHIP is not used when RST_RCV==0.
09600 
09601                                                          When RST_RCV==0, RST_CHIP is ignored.
09602 
09603                                                          When RST_RCV==1, RST_CHIP==1, and PERST*_L
09604                                                          asserts, a chip warm reset will be generated. */
09605     uint64_t rst_val                      : 1;  /**< Read-only access to corresponding PERST*_L pin
09606                                                          Unpredictable when RST_RCV==0. Reads as 1 when
09607                                                          RST_RCV==1 and the PERST*_L pin is asserted.
09608                                                          Reads as 0 when RST_RCV==1 and the PERST*_L
09609                                                          pin is not asserted. */
09610 #else
09611     uint64_t rst_val                      : 1;
09612     uint64_t rst_chip                     : 1;
09613     uint64_t rst_rcv                      : 1;
09614     uint64_t rst_drv                      : 1;
09615     uint64_t prtmode                      : 2;
09616     uint64_t host_mode                    : 1;
09617     uint64_t rst_link                     : 1;
09618     uint64_t rst_done                     : 1;
09619     uint64_t prst_link                    : 1;
09620     uint64_t gen1_only                    : 1;
09621     uint64_t rev_lanes                    : 1;
09622     uint64_t in_rev_ln                    : 1;
09623     uint64_t reserved_13_63               : 51;
09624 #endif
09625     } s;

09985 /**
09986  * cvmx_mio_tws#_int
09987  *
09988  * This register contains the TWSI interrupt-enable mask and the interrupt-source bits.
09989  *
09990  */
09991 union cvmx_mio_twsx_int {
09992     uint64_t u64;
09993     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_int_s {
09994 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
09995     uint64_t reserved_12_63               : 52;
09996     uint64_t scl                          : 1;  /**< SCL signal. */
09997     uint64_t sda                          : 1;  /**< SDA signal. */
09998     uint64_t scl_ovr                      : 1;  /**< SCL testing override:
09999                                                          0 = Normal operation, SCL bus controlled by TWSI core.
10000                                                          1 = Pull SCL low. */
10001     uint64_t sda_ovr                      : 1;  /**< SDA testing override:
10002                                                          0 = Normal operation, SDA bus controlled by TWSI core.
10003                                                          1 = Pull SDA low. */
10004     uint64_t reserved_7_7                 : 1;
10005     uint64_t core_en                      : 1;  /**< TWSI core interrupt enable */
10006     uint64_t ts_en                        : 1;  /**< MIO_TWS_TWSI_SW register update interrupt enable */
10007     uint64_t st_en                        : 1;  /**< MIO_TWS_SW_TWSI register update interrupt enable */
10008     uint64_t reserved_3_3                 : 1;
10009     uint64_t core_int                     : 1;  /**< TWSI core interrupt. Ignored when the HLC is enabled.
10010                                                          Throws TWS_INTSN_E::MIO_TWS()_INT_CORE.
10011                                                          Writes 0 to TWSI control registers IFLG (TWSI_CTL bit 3) to clear
10012                                                          TWS_INTSN_E::MIO_TWS()_INT_CORE interrupt.

10139 /**
10140  * cvmx_mio_tws#_sw_twsi
10141  *
10142  * This register allows software to:
10143  * * Initiate master-mode operations with a write operation, and read the result with a
10144  * read operation.
10145  * * Load four bytes for later retrieval (slave mode) with a write operation and check validity
10146  * with a read operation.
10147  * * Launch a configuration read/write operation with a write operation and read the result with
10148  * a read operation.
10149  *
10150  * This register should be read or written by software, and read by the TWSI device. The TWSI
10151  * device can use either two-byte or five-byte read operations to reference this register.
10152  * The TWSI device considers this register valid when [V] = 1 and [SLONLY] = 1.
10153  */
10154 union cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi {
10155     uint64_t u64;
10156     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s {
10157 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
10158     uint64_t v                            : 1;  /**< Valid bit. Set on a write operation (should always be written with a 1). Cleared when a
10159                                                          TWSI master-mode operation completes, a TWSI configuration register access completes, or
10160                                                          when the TWSI device reads the register if [SLONLY] = 1. */
10161     uint64_t slonly                       : 1;  /**< Slave only mode.
10162                                                          When this bit is set, no operations are initiated with a write operation. Only the D field
10163                                                          is updated in this case.
10164                                                          When this bit is clear, a write operation initiates either a master-mode operation or a
10165                                                          TWSI configuration register access. */
10166     uint64_t eia                          : 1;  /**< Extended internal address. Sends an additional internal address byte (the MSB of IA is
10167                                                          from MIO_TWS()_SW_TWSI_EXT[IA]). */
10168     uint64_t op                           : 4;  /**< Opcode field. When the register is written with [SLONLY] = 0, this field initiates one of
10169                                                          the following read or write operations:
10170                                                          0x0 = 7-bit byte master-mode operation.
10171                                                          0x1 = 7-bit byte combined-read master-mode operation, 7-bit byte write-with-IA master-mode
10172                                                          operation.
10173                                                          0x2 = 10-bit byte master-mode operation.
10174                                                          0x3 = 10-bit byte combined-read master-mode operation, 10-bit byte write-with-IA master-
10175                                                          mode operation.
10176                                                          0x4 = TWSI master-clock register, TWSI_CLK in TWSI Master Clock Register.
10177                                                          0x6 = See [EOP_IA] field.
10178                                                          0x8 = 7-bit 4-byte master-mode operation.
10179                                                          0x9 = 7-bit 4-byte combined-read master-mode operation, 7-bit 4-byte write-with-IA master-
10180                                                          mode operation.
10181                                                          0xA = 10-bit 4-byte master-mode operation.
10182                                                          0xB = 10-bit 4-byte combined-read master-mode operation, 10-bit 4-byte write-with-IA
10183                                                          master-mode operation. */
10184     uint64_t r                            : 1;  /**< Read bit or result. If this bit is set on a CSR write when [SLONLY] = 0, the
10185                                                          operation is a read operation (if clear, it is a write operation).
10186                                                          On a CSR read, this bit returns the result indication for the most recent
10187                                                          master-mode operation, 1 = success, 0 = failure. */
10188     uint64_t sovr                         : 1;  /**< Size override. If this bit is set, use the SIZE field to determine the master-mode
10189                                                          operation size rather than what OP specifies. For operations greater than four bytes, the
10190                                                          additional data is contained in MIO_TWS()_SW_TWSI_EXT[DATA]. */
10191     uint64_t size                         : 3;  /**< Size minus one. Specifies the size in bytes of the master-mode operation if SOVR = 1. (0 =
10192                                                          1 byte, 1 = 2 bytes, ... 7 = 8 bytes). */
10193     uint64_t scr                          : 2;  /**< Scratch. Unused, but retain state. */
10194     uint64_t a                            : 10; /**< Address field. The address of the remote device for a master-mode operation. ADDR<9:7> are
10195                                                          only used for 10-bit addressing.
10196                                                          Note that when mastering a 7-bit OP, ADDR<6:0> should not take any of the values 0x78,
10197                                                          0x79, 0x7A nor 0x7B. (These 7-bit addresses are reserved to extend to 10-bit addressing). */
10198     uint64_t ia                           : 5;  /**< Internal address. Used when launching a combined master-mode operation. The lower 3
10199                                                          address bits are contained in [EOP_IA]. */
10200     uint64_t eop_ia                       : 3;  /**< Extra opcode, used when OP<3:0> = 0x6 and [SLONLY] = 0.
10201                                                          0x0 = TWSI slave address register (TWSI_SLAVE_ADD).
10202                                                          0x1 = TWSI data register (TWSI_DATA).
10203                                                          0x2 = TWSI control register (TWSI_CTL).
10204                                                          0x3 = (when R =  0) TWSI clock control register (TWSI_CLKCTL).
10205                                                          0x3 = (when R = 1) TWSI status register (TWSI_STAT).
10206                                                          0x4 = TWSI extended slave register (TWSI_SLAVE_ADD_EXT).
10207                                                          0x7 = TWSI soft reset register (TWSI_RST).
10208                                                          Also provides the lower 3 bits of internal address when launching a combined master-mode
10209                                                          operation. */
10210     uint64_t d                            : 32; /**< Data field.
10211                                                          Used on a write operation when:
10212                                                          * Initiating a master-mode write operation ([SLONLY] = 0).
10213                                                          * Writing a TWSI configuration register ([SLONLY] = 0).
10214                                                          * A slave-mode write operation ([SLONLY] = 1).
10215                                                          The read value is updated by:
10216                                                          * A write operation to this register.
10217                                                          * Master-mode completion (contains error code).
10218                                                          * TWSI configuration-register read (contains result). */
10219 #else
10220     uint64_t d                            : 32;
10221     uint64_t eop_ia                       : 3;
10222     uint64_t ia                           : 5;
10223     uint64_t a                            : 10;
10224     uint64_t scr                          : 2;
10225     uint64_t size                         : 3;
10226     uint64_t sovr                         : 1;
10227     uint64_t r                            : 1;
10228     uint64_t op                           : 4;
10229     uint64_t eia                          : 1;
10230     uint64_t slonly                       : 1;
10231     uint64_t v                            : 1;
10232 #endif
10233     } s;
10234     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn30xx;
10235     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn31xx;
10236     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn38xx;
10237     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn38xxp2;
10238     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn50xx;
10239     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn52xx;
10240     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn52xxp1;
10241     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn56xx;
10242     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn56xxp1;
10243     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn58xx;
10244     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn58xxp1;
10245     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn61xx;
10246     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn63xx;
10247     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn63xxp1;
10248     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn66xx;
10249     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn68xx;
10250     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn68xxp1;
10251     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn70xx;
10252     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn70xxp1;
10253     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn73xx;
10254     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn78xx;
10255     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cn78xxp1;
10256     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cnf71xx;
10257     struct cvmx_mio_twsx_sw_twsi_s        cnf75xx;
10258 };

10388 /**
10389  * cvmx_mio_uart#_dlh
10390  *
10391  * The 8-bit divisor latch high register in conjunction with the 8-bit divisor latch low
10392  * (MIO_UART(0..1)_DLL) register form a 16-bit, read/write, Divisor Latch register that contains
10393  * the baud-rate divisor for the UART. It is accessed by first setting MIO_UART(0..1)_LCR[DLAB]
10394  * (bit 7) (refer to MIO UART Line Control Register). The output baud rate is equal to the
10395  * coprocessor-clock frequency divided by sixteen times the value of the baud-rate divisor, as
10396  * follows:
10397  * baud rate = coprocessor-clock frequency / (16 * divisor).
10398  * Note that once both divisor latch registers are set, at least eight coprocessor-clock cycles
10399  * should be allowed to pass before transmitting or receiving data.
10400  */
10401 union cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh {
10402     uint64_t u64;
10403     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh_s {
10404 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
10405     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
10406     uint64_t dlh                          : 8;  /**< Divisor latch high register. */
10407 #else
10408     uint64_t dlh                          : 8;
10409     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
10410 #endif
10411     } s;
10412     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh_s           cn30xx;
10413     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh_s           cn31xx;
10414     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh_s           cn38xx;
10415     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh_s           cn38xxp2;
10416     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh_s           cn50xx;
10417     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh_s           cn52xx;
10418     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh_s           cn52xxp1;
10419     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh_s           cn56xx;
10420     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh_s           cn56xxp1;
10421     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh_s           cn58xx;
10422     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh_s           cn58xxp1;
10423     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh_s           cn61xx;
10424     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh_s           cn63xx;
10425     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh_s           cn63xxp1;
10426     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh_s           cn66xx;
10427     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh_s           cn68xx;
10428     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh_s           cn68xxp1;
10429     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_dlh_s           cn70xx;

10492 /**

10496  * FIFO can be written by software and the transmit FIFO can be read by software when the FIFOs
10497  * are enabled. When FIFOs are not enabled it allows the MIO_UART(0..1)_RBR to be written by
10498  * software and the MIO_UART(0..1)_THR to be read by software. Note, that when the FIFO-access
10499  * mode is enabled/disabled, the control portion of the receive FIFO and transmit FIFO is reset
10500  * and the FIFOs are treated as empty.
10501  */

10511 #endif
10512     } s;

10541 /**
10542  * cvmx_mio_uart#_fcr
10543  *
10544  * The FIFO control register is a write-only register that controls the read- and write-data FIFO
10545  * operation. When FIFOs and programmable-THRE-interrupt mode are enabled, this register also
10546  * controls the THRE interrupt-empty threshold level.
10547  */
10548 union cvmx_mio_uartx_fcr {
10549     uint64_t u64;
10550     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_fcr_s {
10551 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
10552     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
10553     uint64_t rxtrig                       : 2;  /**< RX trigger.If FIFOs are enabled (i.e. EN = 1), this field is active and set the trigger
10554                                                          level in the receiver FIFO for the enable received-data-available interrupt (ERBFI). In
10555                                                          autoflow-control mode, the trigger is used to determine when the rts_n signal will be
10556                                                          deasserted. The trigger values are:
10557                                                          0x0 = 1 character in FIFO.
10558                                                          0x1 = FIFO 1/4 full.
10559                                                          0x2 = FIFO 1/2 full.
10560                                                          0x3 = FIFO is two characters less than full. */
10561     uint64_t txtrig                       : 2;  /**< TX trigger. If the FIFOs and programmable-THRE-interrupt mode are enabled, the values in
10562                                                          this field control the empty threshold level at which THRE interrupts are generated when
10563                                                          the mode is active.
10564                                                          0x0 = empty FIFO.
10565                                                          0x1 = 2 characters in FIFO.
10566                                                          0x2 = FIFO 1/4 full.
10567                                                          0x3 = FIFO 1/2 full. */
10568     uint64_t reserved_3_3                 : 1;
10569     uint64_t txfr                         : 1;  /**< TX FIFO reset. Writing a 1 to this bit resets and flushes data in the transmit FIFO. This
10570                                                          bit is self-clearing, so it is not necessary to clear this bit. */
10571     uint64_t rxfr                         : 1;  /**< RX FIFO reset. Writing a 1 to this bit resets and flushes data in the receive FIFO. This
10572                                                          bit is self-clearing, so it is not necessary to clear this bit. */
10573     uint64_t en                           : 1;  /**< FIFO enable. Writing a 1 to this bit enables the transmit and receive FIFOs. Whenever the
10574                                                          value of this bit is changed both the TX and RX FIFOs are reset. */
10575 #else
10576     uint64_t en                           : 1;
10577     uint64_t rxfr                         : 1;
10578     uint64_t txfr                         : 1;
10579     uint64_t reserved_3_3                 : 1;
10580     uint64_t txtrig                       : 2;
10581     uint64_t rxtrig                       : 2;
10582     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
10583 #endif
10584     } s;
10585     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_fcr_s           cn30xx;
10586     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_fcr_s           cn31xx;
10587     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_fcr_s           cn38xx;
10588     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_fcr_s           cn38xxp2;
10589     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_fcr_s           cn50xx;
10590     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_fcr_s           cn52xx;
10591     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_fcr_s           cn52xxp1;
10592     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_fcr_s           cn56xx;
10593     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_fcr_s           cn56xxp1;
10594     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_fcr_s           cn58xx;
10595     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_fcr_s           cn58xxp1;
10596     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_fcr_s           cn61xx;
10597     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_fcr_s           cn63xx;
10598     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_fcr_s           cn63xxp1;

10679     uint64_t elsi                         : 1;  /**< Enable receiver line status interrupt. */

10681     uint64_t erbfi                        : 1;  /**< Enable received data available interrupt. */

10790 /**
10791  * cvmx_mio_uart#_lcr
10792  *
10793  * The line control register controls the format of the data that is transmitted and received by
10794  * the UART. It is always readable and writable.
10795  */
10796 union cvmx_mio_uartx_lcr {
10797     uint64_t u64;
10798     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lcr_s {
10799 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
10800     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
10801     uint64_t dlab                         : 1;  /**< Divisor latch address bit. Setting this bit enables reading and writing of the divisor
10802                                                          latch register (MIO_UART(0..1)_DLL and MIO_UART(0..1)_DLH) to set the baud rate of the
10803                                                          UART. This bit must be cleared after initial baud-rate setup in order to access other
10804                                                          registers. */
10805     uint64_t brk                          : 1;  /**< Break control bit. Setting this bit when not in loopback mode (i.e.
10806                                                          MIO_UART(0..1)_MCR[LOOP] = 0) sends a break signal by holding the UART0/1_SOUT line low.
10807                                                          When in loopback mode, the break condition is internally looped back to the receiver. */
10808     uint64_t reserved_5_5                 : 1;
10809     uint64_t eps                          : 1;  /**< Even parity select bit. Selects between even and odd parity.
10810                                                          1 = an even number of ones is transmitted or checked.
10811                                                          0 = an odd number of ones is transmitted or checked. */
10812     uint64_t pen                          : 1;  /**< Parity enable bit. Enables and disables parity generation and detection in transmitted and
10813                                                          received serial character respectively. */
10814     uint64_t stop                         : 1;  /**< Stop control bit. Controls the number of stop bits transmitted.
10815                                                          0 = one stop bit is transmitted in the serial data.
10816                                                          1 = two stop bits are generated and transmitted in the serial data out,
10817                                                          UNLESS CLS = 00, then one and a half stop bits are generated.
10818                                                          Note that, regardless of the number of stop bits selected, the receiver only checks the
10819                                                          first stop bit. */
10820     cvmx_uart_bits_t cls                  : 2;  /**< Character length select field. Selects the number of data bits per character that are
10821                                                          transmitted and received.
10822                                                          0x0 = 5 bits (bits 0-4 sent).
10823                                                          0x1 = 6 bits (bits 0-5 sent).
10824                                                          0x2 = 7 bits (bits 0-6 sent).
10825                                                          0x3 = 8 bits (all bits sent). */
10826 #else
10827     cvmx_uart_bits_t cls                  : 2;
10828     uint64_t stop                         : 1;
10829     uint64_t pen                          : 1;
10830     uint64_t eps                          : 1;
10831     uint64_t reserved_5_5                 : 1;
10832     uint64_t brk                          : 1;
10833     uint64_t dlab                         : 1;
10834     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
10835 #endif
10836     } s;
10837     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lcr_s           cn30xx;
10838     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lcr_s           cn31xx;
10839     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lcr_s           cn38xx;
10840     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lcr_s           cn38xxp2;
10841     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lcr_s           cn50xx;
10842     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lcr_s           cn52xx;
10843     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lcr_s           cn52xxp1;
10844     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lcr_s           cn56xx;

10865 /**
10866  * cvmx_mio_uart#_lsr
10867  *
10868  * The line status register contains status of the receiver and transmitter data transfers. This
10869  * status can be read by the user at anytime.
10870  */
10871 union cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr {
10872     uint64_t u64;
10873     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s {
10874 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
10875     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
10876     uint64_t ferr                         : 1;  /**< Error in receiver FIFO bit. This bit is active only when FIFOs are enabled. It is set when
10877                                                          there is at least one parity error, framing error, or break indication in the FIFO. This
10878                                                          bit is cleared when MIO_UART(0..1)_LSR is read and the character with the error is at the
10879                                                          top of the receiver FIFO and there are no subsequent errors in the FIFO. */
10880     uint64_t temt                         : 1;  /**< Transmitter empty bit. In FIFO mode, this bit is set whenever
10881                                                          MIO_UART(0..1)_TSR and the FIFO are both empty. In nonFIFO mode, this bit is set whenever
10882                                                          MIO_UART(0..1)_THR and MIO_UART(0..1)_TSR are both empty. This bit is typically used to
10883                                                          make sure it is safe to change control registers. Changing control registers while the
10884                                                          transmitter is busy can result in corrupt data being transmitted. */
10885     uint64_t thre                         : 1;  /**< Transmitter holding register empty bit. When programmable THRE interrupt mode is disabled,
10886                                                          this bit indicates that the UART can accept a new character for transmission. This bit is
10887                                                          set whenever data is transferred from MIO_UART(0..1)_THR to the transmitter shift register
10888                                                          and no new data has been written to MIO_UART(0..1)_THR. This also causes a THRE interrupt
10889                                                          to occur, if the THRE interrupt is enabled.
10890                                                          When FIFOs and programmable THRE Interrupt mode are enabled, this bit's functionality is
10891                                                          switched to indicate the transmitter FIFO is full, and no longer controls THRE Interrupts,
10892                                                          which are then controlled by the MIO_UART(0..1)_FCR[TXTRIG] threshold setting. */
10893     uint64_t bi                           : 1;  /**< Break interrupt bit. */
10894     uint64_t fe                           : 1;  /**< Framing error bit. This bit is set whenever there is a framing error in the receiver. A
10895                                                          framing error occurs when the receiver does not detect a valid STOP bit in the received
10896                                                          data. In FIFO mode, since the framing error is associated with a character received, it is
10897                                                          revealed when the character with the framing error is at the top of the FIFO. This bit is
10898                                                          reset when a reset of the MIO_UART(0..1) is performed. */
10899     uint64_t pe                           : 1;  /**< Parity error bit. This bit is set whenever there is a parity error in the receiver if the
10900                                                          parity-enable bit (MIO_UART(0..1)_LCR[PEN]) is set. In FIFO mode, since the parity error
10901                                                          is associated with a character received, it is revealed when the character with the parity
10902                                                          error arrives at the top of the FIFO. This bit is reset when a reset of the MIO_UART(0..1)
10903                                                          is performed. */
10904     uint64_t oe                           : 1;  /**< Overrun error bit. When set, this bit indicates an overrun error has occurred because a
10905                                                          new data character was received before the previous data was read. In nonFIFO mode, this
10906                                                          bit is set when a new character arrives in the receiver before the previous character was
10907                                                          read from MIO_UART(0..1)_RBR. When this happens, the data in MIO_UART(0..1)_RBR is
10908                                                          overwritten. In FIFO mode, an overrun error occurs when the FIFO is full and a new
10909                                                          character arrives at the receiver. The data in the FIFO is retained and the data in the
10910                                                          receive shift register is lost. This bit is reset when a reset of the MIO_UART(0..1) is
10911                                                          performed. */
10912     uint64_t dr                           : 1;  /**< Data ready bit. When set, this bit indicates the receiver contains at least one character
10913                                                          in the MIO_UART(0..1)_RBR or the receiver FIFO. This bit is cleared when the
10914                                                          MIO_UART(0..1)_RBR is read in nonFIFO mode, or when the receiver FIFO is empty in FIFO
10915                                                          mode. */
10916 #else
10917     uint64_t dr                           : 1;
10918     uint64_t oe                           : 1;
10919     uint64_t pe                           : 1;
10920     uint64_t fe                           : 1;
10921     uint64_t bi                           : 1;
10922     uint64_t thre                         : 1;
10923     uint64_t temt                         : 1;
10924     uint64_t ferr                         : 1;
10925     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
10926 #endif
10927     } s;
10928     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn30xx;
10929     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn31xx;
10930     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn38xx;
10931     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn38xxp2;
10932     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn50xx;
10933     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn52xx;
10934     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn52xxp1;
10935     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn56xx;
10936     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn56xxp1;
10937     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn58xx;
10938     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn58xxp1;
10939     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn61xx;
10940     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn63xx;
10941     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn63xxp1;
10942     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn66xx;
10943     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn68xx;
10944     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn68xxp1;
10945     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn70xx;
10946     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn70xxp1;
10947     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn73xx;
10948     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn78xx;
10949     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cn78xxp1;
10950     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cnf71xx;
10951     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_lsr_s           cnf75xx;
10952 };

10956 /**
10957  * cvmx_mio_uart#_mcr
10958  *
10959  * The lower four bits of the modem-control register directly manipulate the outputs of the UART.
10960  * The DTR, RTS, OUT1, and OUT2 bits are inverted and then drive the corresponding UART outputs:
10961  * dtr_n, rts_n (UART0/1_RTS_L), out1_n, and out2_n.
10962  */
10963 union cvmx_mio_uartx_mcr {
10964     uint64_t u64;
10965     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_mcr_s {
10966 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
10967     uint64_t reserved_6_63                : 58;
10968     uint64_t afce                         : 1;  /**< Autoflow-control enable (AFCE) bit. When FIFOs are enabled and this bit is set,
10969                                                          16750-compatible autoRTS and autoCTS serial data flow control features are enabled. */
10970     uint64_t loop                         : 1;  /**< Loopback bit. When set, data on the UART0/1_SOUT line is held high, while serial data
10971                                                          output is looped back to the UART0/1_SIN line, internally. In this mode all the interrupts
10972                                                          are fully functional. This feature is used for diagnostic purposes.
10973                                                          Also, in loopback mode, the modem-control inputs (dsr_n, cts_n, ri_n, dcd_n) are
10974                                                          disconnected and the four modem-control outputs (dtr_n, rts_n, out1_n, out1_n) are looped
10975                                                          back to the inputs, internally */
10976     uint64_t out2                         : 1;  /**< OUT2 output bit. This bit is inverted and drives the out2_n signal */
10977     uint64_t out1                         : 1;  /**< OUT1 output bit. This bit is inverted and drives the out1_n signal */
10978     uint64_t rts                          : 1;  /**< RTS output bit. This bit is inverted and drives the rts_n signal.6 */
10979     uint64_t dtr                          : 1;  /**< DTR output bit. This bit is inverted and drives the dtr_n signal. */
10980 #else
10981     uint64_t dtr                          : 1;
10982     uint64_t rts                          : 1;
10983     uint64_t out1                         : 1;
10984     uint64_t out2                         : 1;
10985     uint64_t loop                         : 1;
10986     uint64_t afce                         : 1;
10987     uint64_t reserved_6_63                : 58;
10988 #endif
10989     } s;
10990     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_mcr_s           cn30xx;
10991     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_mcr_s           cn31xx;
10992     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_mcr_s           cn38xx;
10993     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_mcr_s           cn38xxp2;
10994     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_mcr_s           cn50xx;
10995     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_mcr_s           cn52xx;
10996     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_mcr_s           cn52xxp1;
10997     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_mcr_s           cn56xx;
10998     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_mcr_s           cn56xxp1;
10999     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_mcr_s           cn58xx;
11000     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_mcr_s           cn58xxp1;
11001     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_mcr_s           cn61xx;
11002     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_mcr_s           cn63xx;
11003     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_mcr_s           cn63xxp1;
11004     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_mcr_s           cn66xx;

11018 /**
11019  * cvmx_mio_uart#_msr
11020  *
11021  * The modem status register contains the current status of the modem-control input lines and if
11022  * they changed.
11023  */
11024 union cvmx_mio_uartx_msr {
11025     uint64_t u64;
11026     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_msr_s {
11027 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
11028     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
11029     uint64_t dcd                          : 1;  /**< Data-carrier-detect input bit. This bit is the complement of the modem-control line dcd_n.
11030                                                          In loopback mode, this bit is the same as
11031                                                          MIO_UART(0..1)_MCR[OUT2]. */
11032     uint64_t ri                           : 1;  /**< Ring indicator input bit. This bit is the complement of the modem-control line ri_n. In
11033                                                          loopback mode, this bit is the same as MIO_UART(0..1)_MCR[OUT1]. */
11034     uint64_t dsr                          : 1;  /**< Data-set-ready input bit. This bit is the complement of the modem-control line dsr_n. In
11035                                                          loopback mode, this bit is the same as MIO_UART(0..1)_MCR[DTR]. */
11036     uint64_t cts                          : 1;  /**< Clear-to-send input bit. This bit is the complement of the modem-control line cts_n. In
11037                                                          loopback mode, this bit is the same as MIO_UART(0..1)_MCR[RTS]. */
11038     uint64_t ddcd                         : 1;  /**< Delta data-carrier-detect. Records whether the dcd_n line has changed since the last time
11039                                                          the user read the MIO_UART(0..1)_MSR. In loopback mode, reflects changes in
11040                                                          MIO_UART(0..1)_MCR[OUT2]. */
11041     uint64_t teri                         : 1;  /**< Trailing edge of ring indicator. Indicates ri_n has changed from an active-low, to an
11042                                                          inactive-high state since the last time the user read the
11043                                                          MIO_UART(0..1)_MSR. In loopback mode, reflects state changes from high to low in
11044                                                          MIO_UART(0..1)_MCR[OUT1]. */
11045     uint64_t ddsr                         : 1;  /**< Delta data-set-ready. Records whether the dsr_n line has changed since the last time the
11046                                                          user read the MIO_UART(0..1)_MSR. In loopback mode, reflects changes in
11047                                                          MIO_UART(0..1)_MCR[DTR]. */
11048     uint64_t dcts                         : 1;  /**< Delta clear-to-send. Records whether the cts_n line has changed since the last time the
11049                                                          user read the MIO_UART(0..1)_MSR. In loopback mode, reflects changes in
11050                                                          MIO_UART(0..1)_MCR[RTS]. */
11051 #else
11052     uint64_t dcts                         : 1;
11053     uint64_t ddsr                         : 1;
11054     uint64_t teri                         : 1;
11055     uint64_t ddcd                         : 1;
11056     uint64_t cts                          : 1;
11057     uint64_t dsr                          : 1;
11058     uint64_t ri                           : 1;
11059     uint64_t dcd                          : 1;
11060     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
11061 #endif
11062     } s;
11063     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_msr_s           cn30xx;
11064     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_msr_s           cn31xx;
11065     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_msr_s           cn38xx;
11066     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_msr_s           cn38xxp2;
11067     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_msr_s           cn50xx;
11068     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_msr_s           cn52xx;
11069     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_msr_s           cn52xxp1;

11074     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_msr_s           cn61xx;

11077     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_msr_s           cn66xx;
11078     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_msr_s           cn68xx;

11196                                                          When FIFOs are enabled, this field provides write data to the receive FIFO. Each
11197                                                          consecutive write pushes the new data to the next write location in the receive FIFO.

11372 /**
11373  * cvmx_mio_uart#_srr
11374  *
11375  * The software reset register is a write-only register that resets the UART and/or the receive
11376  * FIFO and/or the transmit FIFO.
11377  */
11378 union cvmx_mio_uartx_srr {
11379     uint64_t u64;
11380     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_srr_s {
11381 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
11382     uint64_t reserved_3_63                : 61;
11383     uint64_t stfr                         : 1;  /**< Shadow copy of the TX FIFO reset bit (MIO_UART(0..1)_FCR[TXFR]). This bit can be used to
11384                                                          remove the burden on software having to store previously written FCR values (which are
11385                                                          pretty static) just to reset the transmit FIFO */
11386     uint64_t srfr                         : 1;  /**< Shadow copy of the RX FIFO reset bit (MIO_UART(0..1)_FCR[RXFR]). This can be used to
11387                                                          remove the burden on software having to store previously written FCR values (which are
11388                                                          pretty static) just to reset the receive FIFO. */
11389     uint64_t usr                          : 1;  /**< UART soft reset. Setting this bit resets the UART. */
11390 #else
11391     uint64_t usr                          : 1;
11392     uint64_t srfr                         : 1;
11393     uint64_t stfr                         : 1;
11394     uint64_t reserved_3_63                : 61;
11395 #endif
11396     } s;
11397     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_srr_s           cn30xx;
11398     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_srr_s           cn31xx;

11520  *
11521  * The shadow TX trigger register is a shadow register for the TX trigger bits
11522  * (MIO_UART(0..1)_FCR[TXTRIG]) that can be used to remove the burden of having to store the
11523  * previously written value to MIO_UART(0..1)_FCR in memory and having to mask this value so that
11524  * only the TX trigger bits get updated.
11525  */
11526 union cvmx_mio_uartx_stt {
11527     uint64_t u64;
11528     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_stt_s {
11529 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
11530     uint64_t reserved_2_63                : 62;
11531     uint64_t stt                          : 2;  /**< Shadow TX trigger. */
11532 #else
11533     uint64_t stt                          : 2;
11534     uint64_t reserved_2_63                : 62;
11535 #endif
11536     } s;
11537     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_stt_s           cn30xx;
11538     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_stt_s           cn31xx;
11539     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_stt_s           cn38xx;
11540     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_stt_s           cn38xxp2;
11541     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_stt_s           cn50xx;
11542     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_stt_s           cn52xx;
11543     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_stt_s           cn52xxp1;
11544     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_stt_s           cn56xx;
11545     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_stt_s           cn56xxp1;
11546     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_stt_s           cn58xx;
11547     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_stt_s           cn58xxp1;
11548     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_stt_s           cn61xx;
11549     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_stt_s           cn63xx;
11550     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_stt_s           cn63xxp1;
11551     struct cvmx_mio_uartx_stt_s           cn66xx;

11610 /**
11611  * cvmx_mio_uart#_tfr
11612  *
11613  * The transmit FIFO read register is only valid when FIFO-access mode is enabled (i.e.
11614  * MIO_UART(0..1)_FAR[FAR] = 1).
11615  */

11620     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
11621     uint64_t tfr                          : 8;  /**< Transmit FIFO data.
11622                                                          When FIFOs are enabled, this field gives the data at the top of the transmit FIFO. Each
11623                                                          consecutive read pops the transmit FIFO and gives the next data value that is currently at
11624                                                          the top of the FIFO.
11625                                                          When FIFOs are not enabled, this field gives the data in
11626                                                          MIO_UART(0..1)_THR. */
11627 #else
11628     uint64_t tfr                          : 8;
11629     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
11630 #endif
